client signaled to EMT  for assistance. Client was a 15 year-old male found sitting upright, alert and tracking and stating he was dizzy. Client had a chief complaint of dizziness. Assessment revealed no swelling, discoloration, hives, shortness of breath or other signs of anaphylaxis. Client stated that he felt dizzy but denied any pain throughout his body. Client appeared mildly pale but was alert and oriented to person, place, date and event. Client's airway, breathing and circulation were intact. Vital signs: pulse 78, O2 99%, Respirations 12, Blood pressure 118/82, Eyes equal and reactive to light, lung sounds clear bilaterally. Temperature 97.8. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt was seen at ED on5/8 for L sided weakness in the setting of a headache. Pt?s mother reports that these symptoms began 2 days after receiving second dose of Pfizer COVID-19 vaccination in R deltoid. She says that on 5/6, pt complained of L arm weakness during cooking class at school, which was followed by a mild L sided headache later in the day. Symptoms resolved without intervention but recurred on 5/8 with associated L sided facial droop, slurred speech, L arm spasms, and L foot drag.  Pt was seen at  ED for this and had a HA (5/10 in severity) at that time -- workup was unremarkable with a normal head CT, laboratory workup, and resolution of symptoms. Pediatric Neurology evaluated the pt, deemed no further workup necessary, and advised outpatient follow up.   Pt presented again to the ED on 5/10 with concern for full tonic/clonic seizure, witnessed by pt?s mother. Mother reports that she heard pt fall and went upstairs to find pt seizing on his bed -- says that pt had shaking of bilateral upper extremities (in flexed position close to chest) and symmetric lower extremity shaking; eyes were closed without clear focality or eye deviation. Also some drooling, though no incontinence or tongue biting. Episode lasted for approximately 2 minutes; pt was confused and did not recall what happened immediately afterwards but improved within the next 8 minutes. He was taken to the ED by EMS.   By the time he arrived in the ED, he had left sided weakness again. He was given Keppra 1g, placed on EEG, and was admitted. EEG overnight was read "normal" and additional workup was unremarkable. Pt had MRI brain completed showing cortical abnormalities in the R parietal lobe, suspected to be related to recent seizure. MRA showed patent intracranial cerebral vasculature. MRV showed no evidence of dural venous sinus thrombosis. Weakness resolved by the morning and pt was back to baseline on morning of 5/11/21. However, around 9 AM, L sided weakness (face, arm>leg) with associated headache recurred. Mom says that this event was captured on EEG. He was then transferred to our facility. He was placed on pEEG and had repeat labs, imaging completed. Pt did have L sided facial droop, L arm weakness, and slurred speech on arrival, but this resolved within 24 hours. Pt had one additional episode of "wave" of L sided weakness including L sided facial droop and slurred speech at one other time during the hospitalization, but no additional seizure like activity. He was discharged on 5/14 with a normal neuro exam-- some labs (including labs of Rheum and Id workup were pending at time of discharge.) Primary and consulting teams elected to forgo steroids but reconsider should symptoms worsen or return. Pt was readmitted on 5/16-- had an episode of expressive aphasia + headache while at a social gathering; states that he became overwhelmed by the noise. No additional seizure like activity.
LAB_DATA: MRI 5/11: 1.  Area of cortically based FLAIR/DWI hyperintensity in the right parietal lobe. There appear to be some areas of subtle associated restricted diffusion. In the setting of recent seizure activity, this is favored to represent cytoxic edema (due to recent seizure activity). Alternative consideration would be a focal encephalitis, which is felt less likely. No abnormal enhancement is seen in this region. Consider repeat MRI upon resolution of seizure activity to document resolution of imaging findings.  MRI 5/16: 1.  Asymmetric, subtle right cerebral gyral swelling and increased signal. In the associated regions there is prominent sulcal enhancement which may be due to secondary vascular changes (slow flow or hyperemia) versus leptomeningeal enhancement. Findings are more prominent on the prior and favored to reflect encephalitis; autoimmune or infective. Postictal MRI changes remain a possibility, but are felt to be less likely in the absence of more robust seizure activity.  5/11- CRP, ESR, ANA, anti-DNA ds, angiotensin converting enzyme , lupus anticoagulant panel, anti-cardiolipin, anti-beta 2 glycoprotein, CMP, ANCA, anti-Sm, RNP, Ro, La, C3/C4 unremarkable. 5/12 CSF significant for pleocytosis. Meningitis PCR panel, CSF cx, West Nile virus, Respiratory Virus Extended panel, Syphilis, HIV unremarkable.  5/14 quant TB gold pending, anti microsomal thyroid, thyroglobulin pending.   5/16 CBC ESR, CRP, CMP unremarkable.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day of the vaccine I was told that my arm might be sore. I felt sore right away and as soon as I got in the car to drive home I was extremely tired and I slept for the entire six hour car ride home. I was very fatigued that night and then I got a bad headache, fever and it lasted for 48 hours. After that, the headache was less intense and they were intermittent but my arm still hurt and I couldn't lay on it. I was still fatigued for a week. On the fourth day I started to get a weird feeling of vibrations and twitching all over my body. It is especially worse in my temple. It has been a month but I still get the twitching in different parts of my body. My face, arms, legs and temples. It is in different places. It happens less often now, it is not all day but it is still daily and mostly in my head and my legs. I had it happen in my temples last night.  I had my menstrual cycle since the vaccine and it was about three days later than expected. I had a lot of blood clots which was unusual for me. I have had flu like symptoms this week and I have a cough, runny nose and headaches but I am planning on trying to go to the doctor this week.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day after the first dose -I experienced extreme fatigue and  increased episodes of self aware A-fib. I slip into and out of A-fib many times a day, but usually am not aware when it's happening, but after the vaccine, the A-fib signs were much stronger than usual and I was very well aware when I went into A-fib. This became even stronger after the 2nd dose. My electrophysiologist's office said they are getting similar reports from other patients as well. They've scheduled an appt for a holter monitor for Friday May 21st and a video appt with the Dr for June 1st.  Also, within 10 minutes of the 2nd dose I became very dizzy and my heart was racing. The nurse had me stay at the clinic until my heart rate settled down. The dizziness persisted into the next day. The day after the 1st dose, my peripheral neuropathy worsened, and within 8 hours of getting the 2nd dose it became considerably worse than it had gotten after the 1st dose.
LAB_DATA: They have not been run yet. Holter monitor is scheduled for Friday May 21st and a follow up video visit with the electrophysiologist is set for June 1st. (medical oncologist is because of triple negative breast cancer diagnosed in May 2019. I have had chemotherapy, lumpectomy and radiation and there is no sign of the cancer at this time)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received the Pfizer 2nd dose on 9th April. Following day (04/10), I had body ache, fatigue, mild temperature 99.8, back neck and upper arm/shoulder pain. While I recovered from the ache and fatigue the next day (04/11), the neck pain continued for a couple of weeks. On 23rd April, the pain aggravated and I took a 2 Advil's (2 tablets of 200mg each) which made the overall pain extremely critical. The pain was mainly in the neck, upper arm, tingling in the fingers, grinding jaw pain, all symptomatic to a cardiac pain.  I visited the Urgent care and they suggested I rush to Emergency care. See the notes attached. I was detected with Myocardial infraction or Heart Inflammation (as there was an increasing Troponin). They did an Angiogram to detect any blockages but was cleared of all blockages or major heart conditions. Was hospitalized for 2 days and was on observation for any new pains, repeat or increase in symptoms. Heart inflammation continues to be there and I am unable to take any anti inflammatory as that aggravates the cardiac/ MI pain. No prior history of heart disease etc. Will be visiting for repeat tests with the Cardiologist in coming weeks. Since there were no prior heart condition and since this initiated day after the 2nd vaccine, i strongly believe this is a side effect from the vaccine dose.
LAB_DATA: Troponin (04/29), Echo (04/29), Angiogram (04/30), EKG(04/29), Complete blood work (05/29-30), ESR, (05/06) HiSensitivity - CRP(05/06). see attached

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna EUA - Patient who is nonverbal and  received his second COVID vaccine today reportedly developed evidence of discomfort by closing his eyes, gritting his teeth and trying to lay down within 15 minutes of his injection.  This had not occurred w/ his first injection on 4/19/2021.   A medical assistant reported seeing distended right neck and right arm veins, and his family member reported seeing urticaria.  Vitals per MA were bp 97/59, pulse 102, pulse ox 96% on room air.  Upon my arrival, there were no visible distended neck or arm veins, and patient was seated comfortably, upright in the backseat of his family member's vehicle.  There were horizontal linear indentations across his right neck, as though he had been resting his head against the back of his seat, or a seat belt may have been rubbing on it (but seat belt would have been on wrong side).  He was in no respiratory distress.  There were no visible urticaria.  BP was 115/69, pulse 92.  Lungs were clear to auscultation and cardiovascular exam revealed mild tachycardia, regular rhythm, no murmurs, rubs or gallops.  He had received 10 mg of Benadryl through his G tube just as I arrived.    I recommended that patient be observed for 15 more minutes and patient went home without further incident, to go to ER if developed respiratory distress.

Patient presented to the ED with dizziness, fever and heavy vaginal bleeding around 24 hours after receiving her first dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine. She was tested for active COVID-29 infection via nasal swab PCR and tested positive. Upon presentation labs were drawn and her platelet count was found to be 8 on 5/15. Repeat labs were drawn that day to confirm low platelet count and confirmed diagnosis and thrombocytopenia secondary to an immune reaction to the vaccine was suspected. She was admitted and was started on tranexamic acid, medroxyprogesterone, dexamethasone and IV immunoglobulin (Ig) to help treat low platelet count and vaginal bleeding. As of writing, she is still admitted and her most recent platelet count on 5/17 was 16.
LAB_DATA: COVID-19  Nasal Swab PCR: Positive on 5/14 Platelets: 8 on 5/14/21, 6 on 5/15/21, 6 on 5/16/21, 16 on 5/17/21.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received vaccine at 9:35am. Client was immediately syncopal and fell and hit head on floor. RN who administered vaccine noted possible brief tonic clonic activity during syncope. Patient pale and sweating. Client awoke within seconds after fall and was panicked and trying to stand back up. RNs reassured patient and helped patient back into safe lying position. Legs were elevated, VS assessed, ice applied to back of head. No bleeding noted. When patient felt ready and was alert/oriented, nurse raised patient to sitting position and moved into wheelchair. Patient still pale and sweating. Lead RN called EMS due to concern for potential head injury with fall. Patient states that he is lightheaded again and loses consciousness again in wheelchair as RN and EMT are wheeling patient out to be received by EMS squad. EMT supporting patient airway during second LOC - RN notes that airway support (with EMT hands) may be too tight as patient red faced and some throat gurgling. EMT adjusts grip. Patient regains consciousness within 1-2 minutes after second LOC. Patient disoriented - is able to say why he is there and what his name was but cannot remember his age. EMS arrives and takes over care. EMS assessed patient and recommended to transport patient to ED for further assessment. Patient refuses transport to the hospital. EMS squad waits with patient until family member arrives. Patient states family member will transport to hospital. Patient leaves clinic site with family member in car.  First set of vitals/assessment after first LOC at 0940 142/96 BP; 74 pulse; 16 respirations; 97% spO2; 97.7 temp; PERRLA. No bleeding on head; scrape noted L elbow. EMS was called at 9:49am. EMS arrived at 9:54am.   Patient states no major medical history, not on any meds. Patient has fainted one time previously after broken thumb.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Mother approached the post vaccine monitoring desk to notify staff- about patient's appearance.  Staff immediately accompanied the mom to evaluate patient's status.   Staff observed red and diffused splotches his forehead and what appeared to be petechiae bilateral on forearms and hands.  Mom denied any history of allergies. Mom denied a history of allergies and denied any of the symptoms exhibited to today.  Staff asked patient if he was feeling hot, then identified that patient was non-verbal.  His mom then confirmed that patient was feeling hot. Patient was observed with beads of sweat on his forehead.  Patient's jacket was removed.   LPN took his temperature 98.6.  Staff explained to the mother that staff was likely experiencing an allergic reaction and that the treatment of Benadryl 50 mgs capsules ? standing order written by the Dr.  Mom brought a specialized adaptive cup to assist patient in swallowing the caps.  Patient accepted the medication and swallowed both caps.  Continued with an additional 30-minute monitoring with both mom and patient.  Staff notified the mother to contact her medical provider to update information on the this first vaccination, assess reaction causes(s) and to ask for his or her recommendations on whether patient should pursue a second vaccine.  After the second 30-minute monitoring, staff observed the red splotches on the forehead to have dispersed and less localized.  No diaphorases noted. Staff asked patient how he was feeling, he presented as non-verbal however the mother than stated, ?He is OK.?   The observed possible petechiae were present but faint on both forearms and hands. No evidence of shortness of birth.  He was alert to verbal stimuli. Mom did confirm that patient was answering.

54-year-old female with past medical history of hypothyroidism, vitamin D deficiency presenting to the emergency room with bilateral paresthesias of foot and hand.  Patient had received her first more Darner vaccine 3 weeks prior to presentation.  Patient was also noted to have left facial droop and loss of sensation on the anterior tongue.  Patient does report a prior history of cold sores on her mouth.  She was seen by neurologist outpatient where she underwent nerve conduction studies which showed delayed and prolonged F waves consistent with a diagnosis of Guillain Barre room.  Patient underwent a lumbar puncture which revealed markedly elevated protein with very few WBCs consistent with albumin cytologic dissociation.  Patient was started on IVIG for 5 days per neurology's recommendations.  Patient reported improvement in her paresthesias prior to discharge.  Patient was also diagnosed with having Bell's palsy and started on valacyclovir and prednisone per infectious disease consultation recommendations.  Patient underwent an MRI brain which revealed prior trauma/cortical contusion, and mild multiple nonspecific periventricular deep white matter foci of abnormal signal intensity, and no MR evidence of acute infarct.  Also underwent an MRI cervical spine which revealed multilevel cervical enthesopathy with moderate to severe right C4-C5, left C5-C6 and left C6-7 foraminal stenoses.  MRI lumbar spine also reviewed revealed moderate bilateral facet arthropathy at L4-L5 and L5-S1.  Thoracic spine MRI was unremarkable.  Patient's paresthesias improved.  Per neurology's recommendations, patient was discharged home to follow-up with neurology in 2 weeks outpatient.  Patient was also instructed to follow-up with her primary care doctor in 2 to 3 days for hospital discharge follow-up.
OTHER_MEDS: Armour Thyroid, 60 mg, Oral, Daily Tri-Linyah 35 mcg oral tablet, 1 tab, Oral, Daily Vitamin D2 50,000 intl units (1.25 mg) oral capsule, 50000 IntlUnit= 1 cap, Oral

On March 28th, started noticing symptoms. There was pain in my entire right leg, shin swelling; calf- swelling and skin discoloration; and right foot - swelling. On 4/1, I went to Urgent Care where I was seen, evaluated and treated by Dr. She ordered blood tests and an ultrasound within 20 minutes. I had 4 blood clots in 3 veins in my right leg/DVT. My blood platelet value was 267 and the standard range is 130 to 400. They didn't consider it low, but it's still an issue. I was given an injection of Enoxaparin Sodium Injection--1 ml injection twice a day for 5 days, which was started in the ER. I then switched to Pradaxa 150mg pill twice a day. I took that until around the 6th of this month when I noticed my right leg had gotten worse. I was instructed to go back to the urgent care. Another ultrasound was ordered and it showed I still had the 4 blood clots in 3 veins that seems to have worsened, so the meds were not working. He consulted with a vascular surgeon and they put me back on the injection once a day, which I am currently still on. I was told to follow up with my PCP in two weeks and that appt is on Thursday with Dr.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient walked in to the pharmacy for a Janssen Covid vaccination along with family. Patient was advised post vaccination administration to sit in observation for 15 minutes but did not comply and as he was walking away from the pharmacy fainted. Parents reported he did not hit his head and pharmacy was alerted post fall of what had happened. We approached the patient as he was getting to his feet and we advised again for him to come back to pharmacy to sit in a chair for further observation. His parents told us he always has fainting issues post any vaccination or blood work (no prior issue reported to vaccinations on consent form). The patient continued to decline going back to pharmacy and as he walked fainted again, he was able to hold on to shopping cart which lessened severity of fall. Pharmacy staff advised him to remain on floor and after he regained consciousness he was able to answer accurately his name, where he was and what day of week it was. At that time a nurse not employed by Company was shopping near by and began to help care for the patient. The patient and his parents continued to decline calling an ambulance, and after several minutes sat against a wall. He was starting to sweat profusely and heart rate was rapid (approximately 145 bpm per nurse) so we had him remove his coat and provided a cool compress for his head and neck. He was breathing rapidly but was able to slow his respiration upon our direction. The patient did not seem to be improving and the nurse helping advised calling EMS which we did. The patient continued to lose consciousness for brief periods awaiting and during EMS aid. EMS ran the patients blood pressure, blood sugar nd ran an ECG prior to taking patient away to hospital (results unknown to pharmacy as we stayed in area to provide information on patient vaccination administration but had no active assistance  care at that time.
LAB_DATA: Unknown to pharmacy. Pharmacy has attempted several times to follow-up with patient/ Family but have been unable to reach.
CUR_ILL: None reported (Mother mentioned high cholesterol post vaccination administration and reaction)
HISTORY: None reported (Mother mentioned patient being handicap to responding  EMS but never to pharmacy staff or on consent form)
PRIOR_VAX: Patient marked negative on consent form but parents reported post admin reaction to us (fainting).

Cognitive -- severe symptoms began ~3 days after Pfizer 2nd dose.  Extreme disorientation and confusion (transient), memory loss (longterm), extreme lethargy - unable to move, intermittant psychosis (mild, esp. when going to sleep), and anxiety (transient but very extreme, unlike anything I've felt before, not improved by diazepam)  (continued for 10 days then began to improve dramatically followed by alternating relapse on a daily basis for 4 weeks, up to present -- dramatically and stably improved by steroid treatment, returned after discontinuing)   Nerve pain --  began ~1 week after Pfizer second dose. -- tingling, burning throughout extremities, especially fingertips, toes, hips; transient (usually 5 seconds or less). Progressively became more frequent (20+ / day), longer lasting (up to 20 seconds) and more severe (like stabbing or electric shock). Gradually resolved after course of dexamethasone beginning 3 weeks after vaccination.   Sharp inner ear pain -- (both ears) began ~1 week after Pfizer second dose. Rare events (~5x / day), very transient (1-2 seconds) but extremely painful. Continues up to present,  (4 weeks after Pfizer second dose). Also constant popping of both ears beginning week 2 to present, feels like fluid inside.   Adenopathy -- On 4/28/21 noticed massive swelling on left pectoral muscle (contralateral to vaccine injection site), diagnosed as lymphadenopathy, moderately painful. Continued to get worse for 1 week, began dexamethasone on 5/7/21. Dramatically improved, however swelling returned after discontinuing steroid and spread to all lymph nodes, including neck and others. Became extremely painful on 5/14/21, unable to walk due to swelling in inguinal lymph nodes.  Again dramatically improved after steroid injection on 5/16/21.

I received my Janssen vaccine on 3/31/21.  On 4/29/21, I had a virtual appointment with a naturopath about a completely separate health issue (mold illness), and she asked me to check my blood pressure.  I checked my blood pressure using my father in law's at home cuff, and it was 149/99.  I continued to check over several days and had persistently elevated readings, ranging from 122-165/93-107.  My last known normal BP reading was in February of 2021 and was 110/70, which is my typical BP.  I had not checked my BP at any time between February and April because I had no reason to believe it would be elevated.  On 5/2/21, I had a reading of 165/107, which prompted me to go to the ER.  At the ER in triage, my BP was 188/144.  EKG was normal and troponin I was normal.  I was monitored for a few hours with BP around 155/100, and after a dose of Nadolol, my BP came down to 122/79.  I also had chest pain/tightness during this experience, which may have been due to anxiety.  My BP has continued to be persistently elevated (now coupled with anxiety about what is going on, which doesn't seem to be helping the numbers!), and I had to return to the ER on 5/5/21 after getting an at home reading of 180/122 (this was about 1 hour after taking a dose of Nifedipine).  At the ER triage, my BP had come down to 140/109, so they sent me home.  My BP has now remained elevated at around 135-140/95-100, while taking 30mg Nifedipine ER daily.
LAB_DATA: May 2, 2021 - EKG normal, troponin I normal May 5, 2021 - Thyroid panel normal, CBC normal, clotting panel normal, Iron panel normal
OTHER_MEDS: Cimzia, Vitamin B complex, Vitamin D, Vitamin A

About 9 hours after getting my vaccine, I started noticing my temperature rising to ~99.0. About 1 hour later (12 AM), it had risen to ~103. I also noticed my heart rate was extremely high (on average 140 bpm, the highest was 225 bpm); this was also accompanied by chest pains which seemed like they were on the right side of my heart; I also had difficulty controlling my bladder and would randomly start to urinate. I had taken two Advil then slept.  The next day (~9 am) my fever went down but 3 hours later it had gone back up to ~101, I eventually kept cooling myself (removing shirt, fan on high, etc.) and took one Advil and my temperature started to get normal.  For about two days after that, I had pain in my left shoulder - but this was where the injection took place so I wasn't too worried. Currently I am feeling fine, but the initial day getting the vaccine was quite harrowing - I was quite worried I was going to have a heart attack.

I developed a massive GI bleed suddenly 16 days after receiving my second COVID shot.  While I am a UC patient, I have had this disease for over 15 years, and this has NEVER happened before.  Even when in a flare, and even on blood thinners, I have never had a bleed like this.  It required a trip to the ER and a hospital admission for testing and treatment.  In the course of my stay, I learned that Ulcerative Colitis patients are now reporting massive GI bleeds after recovering from COVID itself.  The doctor couldn't rule out the possibility that the vaccine caused the bleed.  I was admitted May 15th and am expected to be released home to recover on May 18th or 19th.  A pelvic/abdominal CT on May 16th showed inflammation in the colon, but a colonoscopy on May 18th showed the evidence of UC was chronic / old disease, while a single significant ulcer was found as the source of the bleed and cauterized.  This occurred while the disease was well controlled on medication, literally out of the blue with no other symptoms besides the bleeding.
LAB_DATA: May 16th, 2021 Abdominal CT; May 17th, 2021 Colonoscopy; multiple blood draws / labs between May 15th and to date May 17th.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 5/17/21 the Patient received the Moderna Covid Vaccine. She presented with a known allergy to PCN and Augmentin. We asked for the patient to sit down and since she had some allergies we asked for her to wait for 30 min. Roughly ten minutes into her wait the patient started to complain of numbness of the face, so we went ahead and gave her a cold bottle of water. About two minutes later the patient began to complain of numbness in the arm along with hives on both arms and neck. At this point the patient looked very flush, disorientated, and acted as if she was going to pass out. I went and sat down with her and I could tell she was uncomfortable for which I got her some ice packs and started asking more questions about her reaction. I could tell the patient was very disorientated and she began to complain of swelling and tightness of the throat.  Once the patient began to complain of throat swelling/tightness. I had call code white and 911 due to the concern of anaphylaxis and pharmacy protocol.

I checked with the pharmacist and he said there were no reports of problems with the medicine. I was experienced strong anxiety due to the constant palpitations.   The anxiety was even waking me up in the middle of the night and giving me insomnia. When I went in for my second vaccine, I told the check in person that I was experiencing anxiety and palpitations.  The person wrote down only anxiety and laughed saying that everyone was a little nervous...I told her that was not it, like at all. I eventually stopped my thyroid medicine because I didn't know what else to do to stop the almost constant palpitations.  I started noticing that they palpitations became less and less over a few weeks.  I made an appointment with my cardiologist but by the time I got in the palpitations were almost gone and no significant problems were found other than the congenital anomalous right coronary artery which I already knew I had. My doctor's office put me on the lowest dose of brand Synthroid 25mcg and I go back in next week for a thyroid check.  A previous check from last month showed that my TSH was 6 but my T4 was normal.

Upon reviewing the patient questionnaire with the patient she indicated that she has fainted with past immunizations about "2yrs ago".   The patient indicated that she has had vaccinations since then and tattoo's without incident.  After administering the Covid-19 vaccination, the patient stated she felt fine and didn't feel like there would be any problem.  I escorted the patient to the post vaccination area for the 15 minute recovery time.   After a few minutes I checked on the patient and she looked fine without signs or symptoms (pale face) of possibly going to faint.  After a few more minutes I heard the patient fall out of her chair.  Upon reaching patient she was laying on the ground and was still out.  After about 5 seconds she awoke and was aware where she was and that she had just received a vaccination.  She stated she felt fine and after about 5 minutes we had the patient sit up when she felt comfortable.  In the mean while a 'Code White' was called and store management had arrived.  After about another 5 minutes and when the patient was comfortable we had her sit upon a chair.  Patient had a very minor bump on her fore-head but was not bleeding.  Patient stated she felt fine but I had the patient remain in the post vaccination area for 45 minutes just to make sure.  The whole time the patient waited she was accompanied with store management.  After 45 minutes I assessed the patient.  The bump on her head looked the same and the patient indicated she felt fine, so I released her to go.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Lot number on card (003B21A) differs from digital Othena record (046A21A). I am not sure why this is and only noticed this as I was reporting in this system.    I was vaccinated in the passenger side of my car in the left arm. As such I had to twist around (with difficulty due to some of my conditions) and the vaccinator had my arm wrenched up and backwards at an angle nearly perpendicular to by body.  After getting my first shot my arm was in immediate significant pain. It started swelling immediately and I was monitored for 30 minutes but told I was not having an allergic reaction so I was likely fine. The pain in my arm worsened into and over the evening and felt as if my arm had been mangled or crushed in some sort of accident. I assumed this normal arm pain. My arm was very swollen. The joints in my hands, fingers, wrist, elbow, we?re also very swollen, red, and painful. The pain at the injection site did not dissipate and I was bruised for several weeks. It was difficult or impossible use my arm and hands (both). I checked in with my doctor after a week. She believed this was an over immune reaction related to my chronic health conditions and believed it would settle itself in time for my next shot and advised me to check in if it did not go away in two weeks. A few days before my next appointment the symptoms had not abated and the pain in my shoulder appeared to be getting progressively worse.  I had radiating pain down my arm at this point and continued swelling all over along with continued swelling and pain in all the joints in my hands, fingers, wrists and elbow. I was advised by my doctor to go to urgent care (I am out of state from staying with my mom). They checked for blood clots and infection and found no signs of either and believed the problem to be an over reaction of my immune system to the vaccine. I was prescribed a Medrol pack. I went to my scheduled second vaccination but was told that they would not vaccinate me after they asked about my reaction to the first shot and looked at my hands and arm. They wanted me to take the medrol pack and reduce the inflammation in my arm before administering the second injection. I took the medrol pack and had mixed success. The first days on the high dose helped reduce the pain and swelling all over but on the days with the lower dose most of the symptoms came back. I contacted my doctor and was prescribed prednisone starting at 40mg/day. At this time the pain in my shoulder was continuing to get progressively worse so I returned to the urgent care. There I received a physical exam and x-ray and the doctor believed I had a shoulder injury (impingement/rotator cuff issue) and bursitis. My shoulder has a stabbing sensation like a knife around the injection site that radiates down the the side of my arm and up over the top front and back of my shoulder. It hurts when I touch it, raise my arm, bend it, try to hold or lift anything, when I am physically active (such as going for a long walk), or sit or lean in certain positions (mostly very forward or back into objects, like the back of the sofa).  All of this makes this area painful but also makes the all over swelling worse and worsens the swelling and pain in my hands, fingers, wrist, and elbow. I have not had any other accident or injury. Due to my chronic health issues I am extremely cautious and have a very precise and conservative exercise regimen (just walking, gentle yoga movements). This shoulder pain very definitely started at the time of the vaccination and has progressively worsened over the course of eight weeks. I have been told to treat it with rest, pain meds, gentle movements, and ice, all of which I have been doing, however the pain and impairment persist. I started the prednisone after the visit to urgent care but on day three began experiencing severe pain in my right eye, face, back of my head, and blurred, unfocused vision. I also had a complete loss of appetite and upset stomach. I was advised by my doctor to immediately stop the medication. I experienced several days of withdrawal symptoms, and the head pain and visual problems have gotten better though they have not completely gone away. The prednisone alleviated some of the arm swelling and pain but the joint pain and swelling in my hands, fingers, wrists, elbows, while a bit better, still remains. While I was diagnosed with arthritis in a few joints (first, second, and thumb knuckles and have had some wrist problems) they were never this severe, as long lasting, or this painful (usually just brief hour long irritation of a knuckle or two). I had not been treated with medication for this ailment because the problem had not been very bad. I am also now experiencing pain in many other joint I have never had problems with (such as other fingers). Sometimes the swelling and pain are debilitating and I am unable to use my hands at all. This had never been the case for me in the past.
LAB_DATA: Doctor Appointments via telemedicine on zoom and via phone (both pcp and rheumatologist). Several appointments and call over past two months. Two urgent care visits with physical exams. One ultra sound of arm. One x-ray of arm. One blood test to check for clots. One medrol pack prescribed. One prednisone course prescribed but could not finish. Conservative home care of rest, ice, gentle movements, and pain reducing meds.
OTHER_MEDS: Topiramate, Spironolactone, multi-vitamin, vitamin D3, Hawthorn berry
HISTORY: Chronic Lyme disease, sero negative arthritis, costochondritis, Raynaud?s syndrome, PCOS, doctor suspected endometriosis (laparoscopic surgery was not recommended), chronic migraine, trigeminal neuralgia (left side), occipital neuralgia (both sides), hemicrania continuia (doctor suspected but unable to take diagnostic medicine), cervicalgia, suspected partial seizures,
ALLERGIES: Doxycycline, levaquin, nsaids (upset stomach and some mild facial swelling), indomethacin, some food intolerances

Patient forehead was slightly red.

On the third visit he used electric stimulation and that started to relieve some of the nerve pain. Next,  I saw an acupuncturist and was needled for those issues. Sexual activity also impossible, erection quality greatly reduced. Many of these symptoms got better but have now returned with my second dose. Second dose has given me significant fatigue, digestive problems again, diarrhea, and reduced erection quality once more. I hope these problems resolve themselves. The vaccine has made going to work very difficult and I will seriously reconsider taking any vaccine in the future.

got the first moderna shot in right arm.   by 10 pm, it felt like my arm had been hit by a hammer at injection site.  I figured that was pretty common, and to be expected.  Sore, but, not alarming.   Then my knee joint on left leg and a bit on right leg began to ache terribly, to the point that I almost buckled on them.   The joint aches moved from a 7 pain on a scale of 10,  down to a 3, and moved to a diffuse body ache for 12 more hours.   Then, the fatigue hit.  I would wake up tired.   go to bed at 10, wake up at 7am,  fall over sideways on couch unexpectedly. and sleep for an hour or two.    It felt like i was severely fatigued.  The fatigue on a scale of 1-10 was about a 7.   It was really debilitating.   The fatigue lasted at a 7 for a full 3 weeks, then a week of 5 level,  then right at 4 week mark lifted quickly in a day.   It was very strange      The fatigue for a month was concerning to me.  I would not want to experience that again.   The shoulder pain was probably what most people experience.  Others I have spoken to have had the joint pain.   But I dont know anyone who had felt 3 weeks of fatigue.
OTHER_MEDS: propecia valtrex  multi vitamins  vitamin D
CUR_ILL: none.  I did have covid in march of 2020
ALLERGIES: allergic to trees and grass,  had allergy shots as a kid.  no drug allergies known.

Now slowly improving but still hospitalized.

No history of fainting with vaccines in the past or allergies. Vitals at 1728: blood pressure 118/72, pulse 82, oxygen 97%. Per client symptoms still there, but improving. Vitals at 1733: blood pressure 120/70, pulse 83, oxygen 100%. Client stated lightheaded resolved, nausea still same. Client denied blurry vision, headache, warmth feeling. Vitals at 1738: blood pressure 118/72, pulse 80, oxygen 99%. Per client all symptoms resolved. Last vitals at 1743: blood pressure 114/80, pulse 76, oxygen 99%. Mother driving client home. Advised to follow up with provider and ER precautions given. After completing 30 min observation client left facility with steady gait at 1750.

I felt tired the day of the shot and slept for about 16 hours. I had no apatite and couldn't get up off the couch because my body felt so bad. It felt like a Crohn's flareup. I called my gastrointestinal specialist and she gave me some medicine to help. I started to get my energy back and felt like eating and drinking again. A week goes by and I started getting a sore throat and the tired feeling again, and started having some vaginal issues. I ended up getting thrush and a yeast infection. I haven't had a flareup in 5 or 6 years and as soon as I took the covid-19 vaccine I got really sick. I thought I should report this just in case anyone else with auto immune disease would have the same issues. I am better and no harm was done other than several medications and a couple of weeks of not feeling well.

Symptoms began around 10 hrs after administration of shot, first a racing heartbeat for a few moments followed by an intense ringing in the ears and legs felt wobbly, quickly progressed to chills feverish for 9 hours. Headache then began for several hours. Tylenol administered by parent/guardian. General malaise and bed rest followed by congestion. Malaise and some nasal congestion lasted for additional 24 hrs.  Thirst treated with electrolyte based-drink and water.
LAB_DATA: None. Symptoms never worsened or amplified to require hospitalization due to what we were told to expect. Ringing and heart palpating was monitored and subsided quickly. All symptoms resolved in 36 hrs.
OTHER_MEDS: Allegra/Zyrtec, 1 tablet daily 25 mg in Spring. Receives allergy shot for environmental allergies once every three weeks. Allergic to pollen, cats, dog hair, horse hair.
ALLERGIES: Pineapple and peach family causes stomach upset but not anaphylaxis.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving the vaccine, increased amounts of heart palpitations were experienced for at least 3 weeks before noticing a little respite in their frequency.  Irregular periods and heavy menstruation have also been experienced. Period following vaccine was heavy and came at a much earlier date than usual for the cycle. The 2nd period after that one started at the end of April and is still going on (as of May 18th). I do not have any history of irregular periods or menorrhagia of this extent.
LAB_DATA: For heart palpitations, echocardiogram was performed  (4/14/21) and a follow-up with cardiologist (4/15/21). For heavy and irregular menstruation, I was seen by my primary care physician as well as at the OB/Gyn clinic (5/14/21).
CUR_ILL: Anemia, heart-related issues such as palpitations and tachycardia
HISTORY: Anemia, heart-related issues such as palpitations and tachycardia
PRIOR_VAX: Tetanus

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Sore arm at injection site, mild body soreness, stomach upset, fatigue, lasted for 48 hours

I had typical symptoms starting approximately 24 hours after the shot.  But 6 days after the shot I had a delayed allergic reaction.  I had hives that over the course of 3-4 days covered my entire body as they rose and subsided in different areas.  I do have one picture of an arm shortly after they started spreading.  This was much worse than in shot 1, where I had a single welt on my arm show up about a week later.
LAB_DATA: I did not seek treatment as I carefully monitored to ensure it didn?t start interfering with respiratory.
ALLERGIES: dairy (only cow), not lactose but a different sugar or protein

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Skin was pinched/bunched upon being administered. Irritation and pain was immediately felt. Swelling, redness, lack of mobility, and pain throughout entire arm has been felt since the injection. At 48 hours out, I developed pain at elbow joint, low-grade fever, and tingling in my pinky finger. I am now 60 hours out, and none of the injection site symptoms have subsided. It appears that it may have been an inadvertent subcutaneous injection, as well as possibly being too high up on my arm.
LAB_DATA: None taken yet. I intend to visit the doctor tomorrow.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: no issues with my first dose, but Feeling fatigued since my 2nd vaccine, and injection site pain, and fingers feel joint soreness, swelling. i still can't get my rings on and has been abnormal for me. fingers feel tight.  facial swelling and edema

A few hours after the injection some bumps formed around the injection site and it has since been very itchy, a little sore and feels like two pea sized lumps around the injection site. Main thing it has been very itchy.

This reaction happened after my second COVID vaccination from PZIFER--not almost immediately the same evening post vaccination I had a mild rash on my neck which resolved immediately and I had some flu like symptoms. But that isn't the reaction. About 9 days after the inoculation, My arm was developing a raised oozing rash which burned--this progressively became worse over the course of several days,, at which point my arm looked like I had a crusted fungal infection (very painful) or necrotizing bacteria--I did see an MD and a dermatologist looked at my arm via pictures--(still have them) It was deemed a vaccine reaction and I was prescribed "Fluocinide" ointment. Eventually my arm healed but it took a couple more weeks,. It was painful and extremely unattractive at the time of reaction.
LAB_DATA: No tests were taken  but there are pictures

In under two minutes, fainted / Believed to be vasovagal syncope; Stomach hurting so bad that felt heart; Chest discomfort; had Diarrhea; Immediate post-injection reaction; Felt very nauseous; Vomited; This regulatory authority case was reported by an other health care professional and describes the occurrence of SYNCOPE (In under two minutes, fainted / Believed to be vasovagal syncope) in a 68-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.     Concurrent medical conditions included Nose congestion (For about 2 weeks.) since February 2021. Concomitant products included PAROXETINE, MELOXICAM, DIPHENHYDRAMINE HYDROCHLORIDE (BENADRYL [DIPHENHYDRAMINE HYDROCHLORIDE]), VITAMIN C [ASCORBIC ACID], COLECALCIFEROL (VITAMIN D [COLECALCIFEROL]), ZINC, ASCORBIC ACID, QUERCETIN (QUERCITIN), LISINOPRIL, FISH OIL (OMEGA 3 [FISH OIL]), CURCUMIN and PHENYLEPHRINE HYDROCHLORIDE (SUDAFED PE) for an unknown indication.    On 20-Feb-2021, the patient received dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 20-Feb-2021, the patient experienced SYNCOPE (In under two minutes, fainted / Believed to be vasovagal syncope) (seriousness criterion medically significant), ABDOMINAL PAIN UPPER (Stomach hurting so bad that felt heart), CHEST DISCOMFORT (Chest discomfort), DIARRHOEA (had Diarrhea), IMMEDIATE POST-INJECTION REACTION (Immediate post-injection reaction), NAUSEA (Felt very nauseous) and VOMITING (Vomited). At the time of the report, SYNCOPE (In under two minutes, fainted / Believed to be vasovagal syncope), ABDOMINAL PAIN UPPER (Stomach hurting so bad that felt heart), CHEST DISCOMFORT (Chest discomfort), DIARRHOEA (had Diarrhea), IMMEDIATE POST-INJECTION REACTION (Immediate post-injection reaction), NAUSEA (Felt very nauseous) and VOMITING (Vomited) outcome was unknown.      DIAGNOSTIC RESULTS (normal ranges are provided in parenthesis if available): On 20-Feb-2021, Abdominal X-ray: unknown Results not reported.. On 20-Feb-2021, Blood test: unknown Results not reported.. On 20-Feb-2021, Chest X-ray: unknown Result not reported.. On 20-Feb-2021, Computerised tomogram head: unknown No fall.. On 20-Feb-2021, Electrocardiogram: unknown Result not reported..     The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown.   For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments.   Concomitant medications included unspecified joint supplement.  It was reported that immediately after the administration of the vaccine, the patient fainted In under two minutes. The  patient reported that there was no  prior history of fainting. After regaining consciousness the  patient reported severe nausea, an episode of diarrhea, vomiting, bad stomach pain which he felt was heart related and went to the emergency room where tests were conducted and he was there for four hours.  No treatment information was provided.; Sender's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I got my second shingles shot which gave me the shingles / suspected vaccination failure; I got my second shingles shot which gave me the shingles; The pain breaking out is something you never forget; This case was reported by a consumer via media and described the occurrence of suspected vaccination failure in a adult patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingles vaccine) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Herpes zoster (Shingles vaccine) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included shingles (the patient had it in his/her 20's) and chickenpox (the patient had it about 6 years ago from the date of reporting and before he/she never had the chickenpox).   On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingles vaccine. In September 2019, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingles vaccine. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Shingles vaccine and less than 2 years after receiving Shingles vaccine, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant), shingles and pain. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure, shingles and pain were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure, shingles and pain to be related to Shingles vaccine. The reporter considered the vaccination failure and shingles to be possibly related to Shingles vaccine. It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain to be related to Shingles vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported by patient himself/herself. The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient was currently in his/her late 60's. The patient stated he/she got 2nd shingles shot which gave him/her the shingles. The patient stated that the pain breaking out was something you never forget, and the physician swears that they did not give the live virus shot. This case was considered as suspected vaccination failure as details regarding time to onset and laboratory test confirming herpes zoster were unknown at the time of reporting. The follow-up would not possible as no contact details were available.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Chickenpox (the patient had it about 6 years ago from the date of reporting and before he/she never had the chickenpox); Shingles (the patient had it in his/her 20's)

A 32-year-old male patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Solution for injection), dose 1 intramuscular, administered on the left arm on 04Mar2021 09:45 (also reported as 12:00) (Batch/Lot Number: EN6199) at the age of 32 years old as 1st dose, single for COVID-19 immunisation. Medical history included seasonal allergies (had it his whole life), sore arm and a family history of shingles (he's had an uncle or something that had shingles before but nothing with his parents). The patient had no allergies to medications, food or other products. Concomitant medication included loratadine (CLARITINE) from Feb2021 for seasonal allergies. The patient wanted to know on what he should expect after receiving the second dose of the vaccine and if he was eligible to receive the vaccine. The patient reported side effects on v-safe. He heard from other doctors that shingles had been reported from the first dose of the vaccine. He wanted to know if shingles would impact the antibodies that he may develop post vaccination. The patient stated that the fact sheet indicated that the second dose should be administered 3 weeks after the first dose, he was scheduled to receive the second dose 4 weeks later and wanted to know if it was safe to receive the vaccine outside the of the recommended time frame. The patient stated that he should be trying to take loratadine everyday (usually takes at night before bed) 1 since he does get kind of bad allergies sometimes. On 12Mar2021 (8 days later after the vaccination), the patient was diagnosed with shingles after breaking out in a rash on his scalp, chest and neck. The patient met his doctor and was recommended to report the adverse event. The patient went through CDC V safe and was provided with an information sheet that from Walgreens that listed the number for Pfizer to call if he needed further information. The patient reported that the noticed the rash (present on his scalp, chin, neck and up around his neck on his right side) on 06Mar2021 or 07Mar2021. The patient stated that the rash onset was "two fold". He noticed it when the back of his head on the right side started to become agitated in Mar2021.  He stated that he sleeps with an eye mask on due to block out the lights from the baby monitor for his 6-month-old and originally thought that it was the sleep mask that was bothering him. He mentioned that on 06Mar2021 or 07Mar2021, he felt like he had a scratch on his scalp and his wife told him that it looked a little swollen. He then reported that the rash on his scalp started to get more and more uncomfortable. When the patient came home on 10Mar2021 around 17:00 or 17:30, he removed his shirt and his wife looked at him and asked what it was. He then reported that the rash appeared on his neck and chin and showed up overnight or that morning. He then stated that the rash on his chin and neck was not painful or anything. The patient then stated that the rash on his head was getting pretty agitated as of 10Mar2021. The patient thought that the rash on his chin, neck, and chest was eczema or heat rash, but thought it was odd because heat rash is normally flat. When he woke up on Wednesday (10Mar2021), the rash was looking worse but was still not bothering him except for the rash on his head. He considered going to urgent care on Thursday (11Mar2021) but didn't follow through. On Thursday night to Friday night (11Mar2021 to 12Mar2021), he couldn't sleep. His rash felt like a sunburn or if like he was hit with a cactus, and the rash on his neck started to bother him. The patient went to urgent care on 12Mar2021, and when the nurse practitioner walked in, looked at him and said that it was shingles. The patient saw 3 people at the urgent care, a nurse, nurse practitioner and a resident doctor as a doctor was needed to confirm the diagnosis. All three of the staff members said that the rash was shingles where the rash was following a nerve pattern. The patient used a cream to treat the rash, he mentioned that he tried diphenhydramine HCl 2%, zinc acetate 0.1% (Benadryl Extra Strength Itch Stopping Cream, Topical Analgesic Skin Protectant; Lot 1790LZ/3, Exp: May2022) briefly on the back of his scalp for 1 night as it was starting to itch and feel weird. He mentioned that it did sting some but didn't think anything of it as sometimes the cream will sting when put over a scab. He also used Aquaphor Healing Ointment Baby Advanced Therapy (Exp: Aug2022, UPC: 0 7214063386 8; NART number 63386), taking slabs of it and putting it over the rash. He then stated that neither did anything. After going to the urgent care, he was put on antibiotics (late described as an antiviral that should clear up in 7 to 10 days since he was young and healthy) that day and essentially said there was not much he could do. The staff also recommended that because he had 6-month-old he should call his son's pediatrician but that his infant son should be okay. He followed up with his son's pediatrician and his doctor, who stated that it should be fine, just to minimize contact with his son. The rash was still visible on his chin, neck and chest. On his scalp was harder to see because of his hair. He stated that going on feel, outside of one spot it felt significantly better. He can now wash his hair and lay on that side of his head without pain. The rash on his neck looks like some are starting to scab over.  He reported that not one patch has disappeared yet, but his wife said that it was looking less red and inflamed. His doctor scheduled a routine blood draw for 08Mar2021 during his physical and stated that he was willing to go through test results as he was unsure what would be helpful, but there were numerous results for each lab test (CBC with auto differential, Lipid panel with reflex to direct LDL, Comprehensive metabolic panel, PSA, total, Urinalysis, and Vitamin D (25-hydroxy) total).  He reported that his doctor had sent him a message in the evening on 08Mar2021 that said "results all normal". The patient didn't require a visit to the emergency room but required a visit to physician office. The patient had no prior vaccinations (within 4 weeks). He stated that there was no history of his parents experiencing an adverse event with vaccines, just the usual sore arm, stuff like that. On 19Mar2021, the pharmacist reported that the events were non-serious. The pharmacist reported that the treatment used for the event was famciclovir. Prior to vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. Since the vaccination, the patient had not been tested for COVID-19. The outcome of the events pruritic rash and erythematous rash was recovering, for shingles was recovered, while unknown for the other events.  Follow-up attempts are completed. No further information is expected.

Remained in waiting room for 15 minutes as per instructions from medical staff. Within approximately 10 minutes of administration, I experienced a wave of warmth that led to a feeling that I would pass out. Called out to nursing staff that I was feeling "dizzy" (didn't know what else to call it). It was not like normal dizziness. Remained seated with legs stretched out to try to combat the feeling I would pass out. Nurses checked my blood pressure and it was in the low 70's. Along with low blood pressure, I experienced temporary hearing loss in left ear, nausea (feeling I could throw up), feeling I could diarrhea/defecate immediately (but held it in for obvious reasons), mental confusion. Nurses called the Emergency Department at my local hospital and told me I should (based on symptoms) be admitted to the hospital. Nurse said my blood pressure wasn't stabilizing at a normal rate of a typical vasovagal reaction. Nurse withheld administering Epipen and monitored the course of my symptoms. EMTs arrived and checked my vitals again in the Ambulance. In the Ambulance, I recall the technician saying my blood pressure was somewhere around 140. This reading is abnormally high for me (my typical blood pressure is around 110). I declined admission to the hospital due to my horrible medical insurance and worry about exorbitant costs. Symptoms did not resolve until approximately 50 minutes after the start of the incident (approx. 9:22 AM).
LAB_DATA: Confusion during this incident leads me to not recall exact medical test numbers. Blood glucose test was fine. However, blood pressure was in the low 70's and then steadily rose to 140 or so. Please contact staff at Health Center (info provided on this form) for exact information.

A 60-year-old female received first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Solution for injection, Lot Number: unknown, Expiry date: unknown), via an unspecified route of administration, administered at an unspecified anatomical location on an unspecified date (age at vaccination was 60 years) as 1ST DOSE, SINGLE for COVID-19 immunisation. Medical history included she had an anaphylactic reaction twice in her life, once to macadamia nuts, and once to "an allergy shot with dust stuff in it". She had a complicated allergy history. Also reported allergies to corn and Benadryl and allergic to an ingredient in benadryl, originally reported as "polypropylene glycol", but later corrected to "polyethylene glycol". The patient was allergic to corn and poly-something in BENADRYL so she couldn't take it anymore. Co-suspect medication included diphenhydramine hydrochloride (BENADRYL). She stated that after the first dose, she had fever of 101F (her normal body temp is 96.8F), a rash on her forehead, and a headache, and noted that on the second day she 'had a little trouble breathing' but said it might be from seasonal allergies. Pretty normal reactions- her normal body temperature was 96.8F had a fever of 101F that's one of the regular side effects and a little bit of a problem breathing- on the second day. Rash on forehead right away, headache too. kept a cold compress and kept switching it every couple of minutes b/c of the fever little pustules. When she put the cloth on regularly it soaked her skin. Rash went away after she had 2 anaphylactic rxn - macadamia nut & allergen shot that had dust stuff in it. She treated the fever and forehead rash with cool compresses and kept switching it every couple of minutes, putting the cloth on regularly it soaked in skin and noted that the rash had what appeared to be 'little pustules" and thought the rash may have been caused by the fever because they resolved at the same time. She had a side effect after the first dose of the vaccine. She asked whether she could receive the second dose and whether she should get the second dose. The nurse that gave her husband his shot said that the reactions to the second dose were more severe. She received the response stating that provided contraindications and discussed potential signs and symptoms of severe allergic reaction as listed in 'CONS-what are the risks of the vaccine (v5.0)' and when they would expect them to occur. Confirmed that fever was commonly reported and that common AEs were more frequently reported after dose 2 in clinical trials (Tables 1-4).  Referred caller to her HCP or vaccination site for additional guidance and monitoring. Confirmed that polyethylene glycol is an ingredient in the Pfizer Covid19 vaccine. She should not get the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine if she had a severe allergic reaction after a previous dose of the vaccine or if she had a severe allergic reaction to any ingredient of the vaccine. The decision to receive the second dose for any other reason cannot be made by Pfizer. They referred her to speak to her healthcare provider about the risks of the vaccine compared to the risks of potentially not being fully protected against COVID-19 infection. Her healthcare provider knew her health situation and had access to information that can better help inform that decision. The caller was unsure if she should take 2nd dose of COVID vaccine. Bendadryl no longer Pfizer but unclear when she developed allergy to it. The outcome of events she had a fever of 101F (her normal body temp is 96.8F), rash and little pustules was recovered on an unknown date. The outcome of the events headache and little trouble breathing was unknown.  No follow-up attempts are needed; information about lot/batch number cannot be obtained. With the first shot, she couldn't describe it, but first 10 to 15 seconds less than a minute started feeling dizzy but not really, states it was like when you first wake up from surgery where you are confused. It was less than a minute and then it was gone. It happened while she was sitting in the seat. It was so strong and then it went away in a minute, it was gone. On 18th September 2020, 3 hrs after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced covid-19, influenza-like symptoms, unwell, tiredness, muscle pain and feels awful. Frozen left shoulder; Limited range of motion and strength; Needle fell off the syringe so the nurse pushed real hard; Limited range of motion and strength; Pain in the left arm; Needle fell off the syringe so the nurse pushed real hard; This is a spontaneous case from the, initially received from other non-health professional to The Agency (reference number: SEQW20-00191) on 20-Mar-2020, concerning a 47-year-old, female patient.  The patient had no medical history.  The patient had no concomitant medications.  On an unspecified date in Oct-2018, the needle fell off the syringe and the nurse pushed real hard to administered to the patient Afluria Quadrivalent [influenza vaccine, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: left deltoid, dose: 0.5 ml (as reported, the full dose was administered), batch number: YF41208 and expiration date: 30-Jun-2019] (explicitly coded as 'Product administration error' and 'Needle issue') for influenza prophylaxis. The device associated with Afluria Quadrivalent was Luer Lok syringe.   On an unspecified date in Oct-2018, unknown amount of time after vaccination, the patient experienced a frozen left shoulder, pain in the left arm and had limited range of motion and strength.  At the time of this report, the pain was improved, but the patient still had limited range of motion and strength. The outcome of 'frozen shoulder' was not resolved.   Product technical complaint (PTC) number 1055541 was assigned to this case.  Based on the Quality Assurance Investigation it was concluded that although a definitive root cause could be not determined as part of this investigation, there was no indication of a systemic manufacturing or syringe raw material defect.  It remains possible that the Luer Lock adaptor may had detached from the syringe as a result of the end user over-torqueing the needle into the attachment prior to administration and caused the Luer Lock to detach. To this, BD has provided a memorandum outlining recommendations for optimal syringe preparation.  This detached Luer Lock was unlikely attributed to a systemic manufacturing defect. On this basis, the final risk rating is 'Low'. Beyond the individual dose, the reported defect presents no residual risk to the remainder of the batch as is now expired and should no longer be available for patient administration. This was the only PTC for lot YF41208 and a detached Luer Lock for the NH 2018 - 2019 Influenza campaign. All material passed required testing against approved specifications for each component and was found to be satisfactory for use. There were no damages noted on the transport.   This case was assessed as non-serious, per reporter.   The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Afluria Quadrivalent.  Follow up information received from other non-health professional to The Agency (reference number: SEQW20-00190) on 20-Mar-2020: Primary reporter information updated. Details about damaged syringe was provided. The narrative was amended accordingly.  Follow up information received from PTC group on 05-May-2020: Quality Assurance Investigation results were provided. The narrative was amended accordingly.   Company comment: The patient developed periarthritis, muscular weakness, injected limb mobility decreased and pain in extremity on an unknown date, reportedly within the same month, after vaccination with the suspect product, Afluria Quadrivalent. Chronology is plausible. Reportedly, the needle fell off the syringe and the nurse pushed real hard to administered to the patient Afluria Quadrivalent (explicitly coded as 'Product administration error' and 'Needle issue'). No information regarding medical history and concomitant medication was provided. Product administration error is assessed as not related to Afluria Quadrivalent and device Luer Lok syringe per company conventions, while for all other events as unlikely related due to medication error and needle issue. (''unlikely related'' defaults to ''related'' in the safety database for reporting purposes) For needle issue, which is considered as PQC, causality is assessed as related to device Luer Lok syringe and not related to Afluria Quadrivalent per company conventions. Causality for the events of 'painful L arm', 'injected limb mobility decreased', 'muscular weakness upper limb' and 'frozen shoulder' are assesses as related to device Luer Lok syringe.; Sender's Comments: The patient developed periarthritis, muscular weakness, injected limb mobility decreased and pain in extremity on an unknown date, reportedly within the same month, after vaccination with the suspect product, Afluria Quadrivalent. Tenderness from injection; Part of the product did not reach the muscle; Part of the product was running down his skin in the arm; The vial stopper felt loose when the syringe was inserted; This spontaneous case from the  was received on 10-Sep-2020 from a consumer via The Agency (reference number SEQW20-01453) and concerned a 58-year old, male patient.   The patient's concurrent condition included ulcerative colitis in remission. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported.   On 09-Sep-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Afluria Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, dose: less than 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: not reported) for influenza prophylaxis. The vial stopper felt loose when the syringe was inserted (explicitly coded as 'Product use issue') and part of the product did not reach the muscle (explicitly coded as 'Incomplete dose administered'). The healthcare professional did not stop giving the vaccine when encountered pressure. Part of the product was running down patient's skin in the arm (explicitly coded as 'Accidental exposure to product'). The device associated with Afluria Quadrivalent was Luer Lok syringe. The batch number reported was P100247218.   On the same day, after receiving Afluria QIV, the patient experienced tenderness. There was no side effect on the skin.  At the time of follow up reporting on 15-Sep-2020, the outcome of the event tenderness was not reported.  Quality Assurance (QA) investigation of Afluria Quadrivalent, batch number P100247218 (PTC number: 1066578) found that after review of the final investigation, there was no internal root cause identified and the manufacturing process was not at fault for the filed complaint. The facility, methods and controls used for the processing of this batch were in conformance with master batch record requirements. A review of the executed batch records indicated the batch was manufactured according procedures. From the review of the details for this complaint multiple potential faults were identified where user handling was the most likely cause for this PTC, therefore this was the most likely cause of this complaint. It is concluded that there was no requirement for any market action based on all information received, as there was no patient safety risk and the overall defect rate for leaking syringe/luer lock connection was 1 Defects/Million Syringes distributed. No additional actions were required for Afluria Quadrivalent for batch P100247218.  The reporter assessed the event tenderness to be related (reported as tenderness from injection) to Afluria Quadrivalent.  The reporter assessed the case as non-serious.  This case has been entered onto Seqirus's manufacturing quality assurance tracking database and allocated reference number 1066578.  Additional information received on 16-Sep-2020 from a pharmacist and processed together with an additional information received on 22-Sep-2020: New reporter added. The case and events updated to medically confirmed. More information on 'product use issue' provided. Product Technical Complaint (PTC) number and additional reference number added. Event of 'Exposure via skin contact' removed. Narrative amended accordingly.  Case updated on 10-Oct-2020: Correction made to information received 16-Sep-2020: Vaccine indication was recoded. Also, additional information received on 31-Oct-2020 from Product Technical Complaint (PTC): QA investigation provided. Narrative was amended accordingly. A syringe collar broke when a staff member was vaccinating a patient with a vaccine, slicing the staff members finger.; A syringe collar broke when a staff member was vaccinating a patient with a vaccine, slicing the staff members finger.; This spontaneous case from the  was received on 29-Sep-2020 from other non-health professional via Product Technical Complaint (PTC) group and concerned a staff member of unknown age and gender.  The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported.   On an unknown date, when a staff member was vaccinating a patient with Afluria Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine), a syringe collar broke and sliced the staff member's finger (explicitly coded as 'Syringe broke'). The device associated with Afluria Quadrivalent was Luer Lok syringe. The batch number reported was P100230205.  The outcome of event 'laceration of finger' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment to Afluria Quadrivalent.  This case has been entered onto manufacturing quality assurance tracking database and allocated reference number 1067172.  An investigation into batch P100230205 revealed that the most probable root cause of broken finger flange on was due to packaging equipment at the fill/finish facility. Shipping of the product was also a possible root cause for the event, as it could not be completely ruled out. Since the packaging line was the most likely root cause, the root cause had been assigned as 'Equipment Malfunction' and the complaint was justified. It was concluded that there was no requirement for any market action based on all information received, as there was no patient safety risk and the overall defect rate for broken finger flanges is 1 Defect/Million Syringes distributed. No additional actions were required for Afluria PFS Drug Product or for batch P100230205.  Additional information was received on 10-Nov-2020 from manufacturing quality assurance department: Quality Assurance Investigation Results were provided. Batch number was added. Narrative was amended accordingly.  Company comment: A syringe collar broke when a staff member was vaccinating a patient with Afluria Quadrivalent, slicing the staff members finger. Laceration was a result of syringe issue making causality unrelated to the product, while device issue was assessed as unrelated per company conventions. SYMPTOM_TEXT: At approximately 4:15 PM, a pt stated feeling light-headed and clammy.  Pt was assisted to a wheelchair and moved to a cot.  Pt's vital were assessed. HR:120, RR:20, SaO2: 98.  Ot appeared flushing and pale.  Lung sound were clear and equal bilaterally.  Pt sat for 30 minutes and stated she wanted to go to the hospital POV.  Pt's VS were reassessed.  HR: 106, BP: 136/86, RR: 20, SaO2: 98%.  Pt signed  form.  Pt was assisted out of the clinic by wheelchair.

Prior to vaccination the patient reported that in the past he had passed out after giving blood. About a minute after administering the COVID-19 vaccine the patient reported feeling dizzy. He then passed out in the chair. We safely moved the patient to the floor. Then within approximately 15 seconds the patient sat up and then stood up on his own. We asked the patient to then be seated in the chair while he recovered. We called 911 as soon as he passed out. Patient was somewhat confused initially but quickly regained his bearings. He began sweating and said he was very hot. We checked his blood pressure and it was 100/80. Patient continued to recover and said he was feeling better. We had him wait until EMTs arrived. He told them he did not need any care. We took his blood pressure again and it was now 110/75. He said he felt well to go to the EMTs and pharmacist.

In January I started complaining to my husband about a noise at night - low hum. I thought it was related to our home (freezer, pipes, gas, etc), but my husband couldn?t here it.  The sound persisted, and I noticed it also when we stayed elsewhere so I then recognized it as tinnitus.   Interestingly, after my husband got his covid vaccine he started to have tinnitus as well, so we began to question if this is a side effect of the vaccine.  It is now May, and my tinnitus persists.
OTHER_MEDS: OTC Prenatal multivitamin, additional vitamin D3 2000 units, intermittent probiotic and magnesium supplement.

Patient is a 17 yo male with no hx asthma who presented to medical center ED as transfer from facility with pleuritic chest pain and fever x1 day. Recent history of second covid vaccine on Friday (5/14). Patient reported associated fatigue, headache and muscle aches late Friday into Saturday (5/15). Sunday patient reported a fever (101 F) and chest pain with deep inspiration. No associated SOB, increased work of breathing or abdominal pain. Was seen initially at urgent care and then referred to facility for "an abnormal EKG."    Pertinent findings at facility: troponin 0.31, EKG wnl, rapid covid negative, ESR 9, CK 134, D-dimer <150, WBC 12.4 w/ left shift. Transferred to medical center for further workup.   While in medical center ED, troponin 1.59. EKG rSR' leads V1-V3 w/o ST segment elevation. MISC tier 1 studies drawn. Cardiology consulted - admit for observation, myocarditis infectious workup, echocardiogram and  During his time in the ED, patient continued to have pain with deep inspiration as well as when he had to yawn. He other wise felt fine. Vital signs normal throughout out time in ED.  His troponin continued to rise, with max of 14, so decision was made to start IVIG and steroids. His troponin fell over the next day. He remained stable from a clinical standpoint, and symptoms had resolved by the morning of 5/18. At time of filing, patient is still hospitalized at medical center, with further labs and imaging pending.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 15 min. Observation ended at 4:08pm; patient complained of minute skin elevation on his left lower arm radiating to his upper arm. Patient voiced no itchiness on his arm. Benadryl P.O. given at 4:15pm. At 4:45pm, patient verbalized of slight dizziness. ER notified for further evaluation. Patient's vitals as follows: 182/101 ; HR-105/min; SPO2-96-98%. To ER per stretcher. Patient is alert and oriented, accompanied by ER nurse. ED Note: Patient is a 39 y.o. male with no significant medical history presents with an allergic reaction after his second Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine dose earlier today. Patient and his mother reports that patient received second dose of Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine shot today at about 15:50. Before the 15 minutes observatory period was complete, patient and his mother noted that his arms became red, he was diaphoretic, and he developed "'chills and goosebumps."  He denies itchiness or shortness of breath. He was given Benadryl at 16:10 today and requested a bed to observe him. His reaction prompted transfer to the ED. Patient reports he feels improved at this time. He denies taking any new medications and notes he had no issues after the first vaccination dose. Reevaluated patient. Patient feels improvement and is ready for discharge. The patient is comfortable with further observation of his symptoms at home.  I discussed our workup, answered all questions and made sure there were no other concerns.  I provided counseling about standard home and self-care measures and advised on standard return precautions including new, persistent, or worsening / concerning symptoms. Discharge Meds: famotidine 20 mg BID, fexofenadine 180 mg daily, prednisone taper x 6 days.

I threw up within an hour of the first dose of the vaccine. Three days after the vaccine I had extremely swollen Lymph nodes I have been suffering from severe fatigue and low white blood cell counts. My RBC and WBC count was dropping within one week after the vaccine. My Platelet count was also dropping. My intestines were inflamed, and I have suspected Endometriosis. I now have Hypokalemia as well. I have never had that before. I was in the ER twice in March with low Potassium even though I was taking some Potassium. I later had severe abdominal pain and I had inflamed intestines which were confirmed during an ER visit,  I have muscle and joint aches and I have been diagnosed with Osteoporosis since getting the vaccine. I have tried multiple medications to control my hypertension and nothing has worked yet. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I gave a 21yo male a Janssen vaccine approximately 508p on 5/15. Vaccination was routine and the patient walked to the observation chair.  Around 520p, an acquaintance of the patient came up asking for a vomit bag.  I went out to the observation chair with a small trash can and paper bag and at 522p the patient stated he felt dizzy and vomited.  My technician stayed with the patient, and I went to the pharmacy to grab paper towels, a new mask, and a bottle of water. I came back and asked the patient how he was feeling (524p). He said that he felt much better after vomiting. I asked if he wanted a cold pack or water, and he took the bottle of water and denied the cold pack. I asked him to continue to stay for observation. At 537p, I went out to see how the patient was feeling.  He stated he was feeling better and was no longer dizzy. At 538p (30 minutes after vaccination) the patient stated he felt comfortable to leave and continue shopping in the store with his acquaintance.
