LAB_DATA: Patient is a 17-year-old male with no significant past medical history who presents with 1 day of sudden onset sharp chest pain, found to have diffuse ST elevation on EKG as well as elevated troponin consistent with acute myopericarditis. Must consider whether presentation is related to patient having received his 2nd COVID-19 vaccine 2 days prior to presentation. COVID-19 spike protein antibodies are positive but no evidence of prior infection. However, will also evaluate possible viral causes for the myopericardial inflammation. Patient is currently hemodynamically stable but admitted to the PICU for telemetry due to risk for dysrythmia given myocardial inflammation. SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day after the vaccine I was working and later in the day I started to feel dizzy. Within an hour and a half I could not stand up and I was very dizzy. My coworkers said my eyes rolled back in my head. The ambulance transported me to the ER and my Blood Pressure was at 80 Systolic. I was given fluids and I was discharged after five hours. I still couldn't work the next day and I was still really tired for the rest of the week. It seemed to take a couple of weeks to feel normal but the fatigue was extreme for the first week after the episode of dizziness. I have two autoimmune diseases and a history of blood clots so I might not have gotten the Janssen vaccine if the risk was known. The blood thinner I was taking at the time might have helped but my blood pressure on discharge was still only 110/60.

Initial noticeable symptom: rapid sinus clearing and nasal drain five minutes after shot, followed by noticeable but bearable dizziness & nausea five minutes after that (it seemed to sweep upward from the back of my neck, like being on a carnival ride with a lot of G force).  Dizziness and nausea resolved completely after about five minutes.  Sinuses remained clear for 36 hrs. (being spring, I have chronic sinus congestion this time of year due to mild seasonal allergies, so this was noticeable).  Stabbing, shooting arm pains, short in duration but painful enough that I had to let my arm hang limply at my side- these were unlike any I have experience before- began about an hour after vaccine and continued off & on for approx. 72 hrs.  Headache, nausea, exhaustion were present off and on from several hours after vaccine until about 72 hrs. later, when they resolved.  36 hrs. after vaccine painful, red uveitis set in in both eyes.  I have autoimmune issues and am prone to uveitis flares and immediately began taking my prescription prednisolone acetate 1% eye drops 4x day; pain and redness resolved within 36 hrs. of onset.  I tapered off eyedrops for the next week.  I did not report any of these symptoms to the clinic and have had no other side effects since.  I go for my second shot today, will see what happens.
HISTORY: HLA-B27 positive, diagnosed with Reactive Arthritis 10+ years ago.  Prone to uveitis flares.  Also dx connective tissue disorder Ehlers Danlos syndrome, specific type unknown.
ALLERGIES: some food sensitivities but no severe allergies (nightshades, dairy, wheat, sugar)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Note: the Lot # could be - ED7534 - difficult to say. I got the shot around 5 pm and felt fine until about 01:00 AM. I started having chest pains in the muscle. I took 1/2 an alprazolam tablet  but it didn't do anything. My chest felt tighter but I was still able to get a full breath through everything though. My throat got scratchy and tight. Both of my arms were feeling tingly. I have bone spurs, I associate tingling in the arm with bone spurs with my nerves and what they pressed. The vaccine seemed to make everything every chronic issue I have flare up. Around 2 am I took reg. strength Tylenol and the antihistamine because I take those twice a day regularly for year around allergies. I also took a Benadryl in case I was having an allergic reaction Around 2:30 am, my tongue started feeling kind of tingly especially on the right side. A lot of the chronic pain are worse on the right side of my body. I was feeling kind of nauseated. Around 3 am the tingly sensations spread up my face mostly on right side and I had pain in my teeth -  not unusual because of the nerve damage that has happened on the right side.  I had a hysterectomy some years ago and since then I've had cluster of nerves in my lower right abdomen that is the epi center of a lot of my nerve pain and that cluster started throbbing and sending it up into my chest and that started acting up and it runs up right to my left breast. This usually doesn't all happen to me at once but these are things that have happened to me before. I eventually went to sleep. NExt day,  About 2:30 pm, I got out the pulse/ox thing - Oxygen: 97 - even though my heart was kind of pounding - my pulse was 65 and 60. I called my doctor's office and got transferred to COVID hotline at Hospital and I talked to nurse there who told me the vaccine can cause inflammation throughout the body which could cause the exacerbation of all my usual symptoms and why they all were flaring up all at once. All the doctors in my doctor's office were busy and she found a Physician's assistant who could talk to me and he told me what she had told me. And to be prepared for me to be prepared for it for the second dose. It took almost until it was time for my second dose of vaccination for the symptoms to dissipate. It was a very slow process. It was four days before I was going to get my second one before I felt like the symptoms had gone. I talked to my doctor before getting second one and she gave me the go ahead to get it.

Symptoms are variable but some combination troubles me every day since March 6, excepting the twelve days I was on the Prednisone prescription.  In general, pain increases during sleeping hours, when I grow stiff and less flexible. I wake several times during the night (almost hourly) dry-mouthed. I don't know if pain wakes me or not. I rise with great difficulty and hobble to the bathroom.  Mornings are the worst part of the day, but I find if I keep moving, I loosen up and the general inflexibility goes away, and to some degree, so does the pain. It is never entirely gone. I also find that the pain seems to generally occur during movement and not at rest, although the pelvic pain and upper leg pain has and does occur while at rest.  The most regularly-occuring pain is hamstring and shoulder (shot locations). Rising from a laying or seated position has always been the most difficult.  Lately, pelvic pain has been rare, and knee pain intermittent.

Second shot was received on 4/30/2021. My very regular and predictable period was due on 5/7/2021. The shot delayed my period by 1 week and it started on 5/14/2021. 5 pregnancy tests were taken in that week and all were negative. I track and chart my cycle closely because of my endometriosis so I'm able to plan my life around my debilitating symptoms. I did have the typical feeling really bad and stuck in bed the day after the vaccine. However, the day after that, 2 days after the shot, my typically debilitating premenstrual symptoms were stopped and I felt great, better than I have in a long time. Until the day before my period started on 5/13/2021 when I got a migraine (not typical for me) The migraine continued for 2 days. I was bed bound for those 2 days between the period pain and the migraine. The 3rd day and the last day of the period I felt much better and was able to resume regular activities. My period typically last for 5 days and is usually very heavy in the first 2-3 days. This period only lasted 3 days and was much lighter flow than is normal for me.

Briefly, patient is an otherwise healthy 16-year-old female who presents with 12 days of epigastric pain in the setting of getting her 2nd COVID vaccine on 5/5. Did have fever and vomiting during the first 24 hours which has since subsided, but the abdominal pain has persisted. She has had a reassuring work up through her PCP but presents with continued pain. Labs overall reassuring with normal LFTs and lipase. Awaiting RUQ US and urine at this time.   0100: Family requesting discharge home. does not want to wait for US as they have an outpatient US scheduled for Thursday 5/20.  Temperature: 36.6 DegC (05/18/21 01:14:00)  Systolic Blood Pressure: 118 mmHg (05/18/21 01:14:00)  Diastolic Blood Pressure: 60 mmHg (05/18/21 01:14:00)  Heart Rate: 80 bpm (05/18/21 01:14:00)  Respiratory Rate: 20 br/min (05/18/21 01:14:00)  Oxygen Saturation (SPO2): 98 % (05/17/21 20:28:00)  On re-evaluation, patient is awake, alert and well-appearing. She has remained afebrile, with normal vital signs for age. Reports improvement in symptoms, has tolerated PO and feel that she is appropriate for discharge home. Anticipated course of illness reviewed. Supportive care (rest, push fluids) discussed. Reasons to return to the emergency department discussed in detail. Written instructions provided. All questions answered. Parents expressed understanding and agreement with this plan. Patient was awake, alert and well-appearing upon discharge home from the emergency department.   Final Diagnosis   1. Epigastric pain R10.13  2. Adverse reaction to vaccine constituent T50.A92A

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received 1st Pfizer dose on 4/2/21. On (or about) April 15th (13 days later) I  had a sudden sensation and felt the back of my knees and the bottoms of my feet overcome by a strong numbing sensation as if they had fallen asleep. This persisted for a half a day before suddenly going away. This is not a sensation I've ever experienced prior. I drank a lot of water and took magnesium for fear I was dehydrated. The sensation subsided later that day.   Received 2nd dose of Pfizer on 4/21/21. On (or about)  May 14th (21 days later) and another episode has started, however this has lasted for several days now persistently. This time a numbing sensation only resides on my left side starting from just above the back of my knee down  the back of my calf and into the bottom of my foot. The sensation sometimes feels like a vibrating buzzing sensation, to a tingling/numbness. I also feel a numbness sensation on the bottom of my foot with each step taken. In addition, I have a slight numbness in my left arm that radiates from the shoulder, into the armpit, along the inner elbow, and into the palm of my hand and down to my fingers. My right side is not affected. The arm sensation comes and goes.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Briefly, patient with history of asthma and food allergies, presenting with hives, nausea, and swelling, in setting of receiving Covid vaccine 36 hours ago. Family had given benadryl and zyrtec without improvement, and symptoms were worsening to presents for evaluation.     My exam (after Epipen) showed: Gen: nontoxic appearing; HEENT: no lip/tongue/uvular edema, PERRL, EOMI, normal conjunctiva, neck supple without LAN; Card: RRR, no murmur, good perfusion; Lungs: CTAB, good air entry, no increased WOB, no wheezing; Abd: soft, non-tender, non-distended, no masses; Ext: warm and well perfused, moving all extremities; Skin: hives over hands, arms, abdomen, and legs, including between fingers and on soles of feet     Patient presenting with allergic reaction after Covid vaccine, could be more benign allergic reaction such as urticaria multiforme, but given constellation of symptoms and history of severe allergic reaction in past, will treat as anaphylaxis. Therefore given Epipen, steroids, and will plan for observation.   Observed 4 hours and continued to be well appearing without symptoms of rebound anaphylaxis. Therefore, patient safe for discharge to home with supportive care and PCP follow up. Given Rx for benadryl and steroids, refilled Epipein. Family in agreement with plan and verbalize understanding of signs and symptoms to return to care.  Final Diagnosis  1. Anaphylaxis T80.52XA

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 05.17.21 patient  received his first dose of the Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine (lot # EW0182 exp. 08/2022). Client's mother signaled to EMT that they needed assistance. EMT and RN responded. Client was a 16-year-old male found sitting upright and leaning forward while alert and tracking. Client had a chief complaint of ringing ears and uneasiness. Client stated that he began to notice his ears ringing a few minutes after observation began. Client's mother was unable to console the client prompting her to calmly wave for assistance. This was the client's first dose of the Pfizer vaccine. He and his mother both deny any medical history, allergies, or regular medication use. Assessment revealed no hives, rashes, discoloration, swelling, shortness of breath or other signs of anaphylaxis. Client complained of unspecified uneasiness while leaning forward but exhibited no accessory muscle use. Client denied any pain throughout his body. Airway, breathing and circulation were intact. Client stated that he was "nervous" before receiving his vaccine today due to stories he had heard from his peers. Client then stated that he felt like he "couldn't move [his] hands" despite there being no obvious range of motion compromise. Vitals at 1332 were pulse 76, O2 100%, lung sounds clear bilaterally, alert and oriented to person, place, date and event, respirations 20. Client and mother both consented to an additional 30 minutes. Client was assisted from his observation chair to a bed by EMT and mother and stayed there for the remainder of his observation. After approximately five minutes of lying down, the client stated that he felt "much better." Remaining vitals: 1337 - 118/78, O2 99%, Resp. 16, HR 76, 1349 - 110/76, HR 72, O2 99%, Resp. 16. 1402 118/78, O2 100%, HR 72, Resp. 16. Client's mother was provided with all relevant vaccine information and instructed to seek medical attention if further concerns arise in the evening. Client denied EMS transport. Client completed his observation at 1402 and departed with his mother at 1402 in positive disposition with steady gait asking his mother if he could go out and "skate".
NO ADVERSE REACTIONS. ADMINISTRATION DEVIATION: UNAUTHORIZED AGE GROUP

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 17 y.o. male who presents with chest pain, elevated troponins and diffuse ST elevations concerning for pericarditis vs myocarditis admitted for cardiac monitoring and evaluation. Pt states he has had 1 day of sudden onset L shoulder pain and chest pain. Endorses dyspnea due to pain with deep breaths, denies tachypnea, nausea/vomiting, diaphoresis. Endorses mild chills and aches after COVID vaccine 3 days prior to onset of symptoms, denies any fever, URI symptoms, diarrhea, rash, known COVID contacts. Pain continued to worsen and spread across his chest, causing presentation to ED this afternoon. No history of PE, DVT, long travel, recent surgery, malignancy, alcohol or cocaine use. Significant cardiac history in family: dad with CAD w/LAD blockage, both parents with hypertension.    At ED, labs notable for elevated troponin 0.456, repeat 0.67 and diffuse ST elevations on EKG concerning for pericarditis. COVID neg, CXR unremarkable, blood cx drawn, no abx started. Patient was given toradol for pain with minimal improvement. Peds cardiology was consulted and patient was transferred to different ED for further care.   At different ED, repeat EKG showed similar diffuse ST elevations in I, II, aVL. Repeat troponins uptrending (4.91), proBNP 562, ESR 43, CRP 18. Mildly tachycardic but otherwise hemodynamically stable. Given tylenol for pain. Cardiology recommended admission for trending troponins, echo and cardiac monitoring.  CV: Troponins were trended every 12 hours with a max of 4.91.  His last troponin checked on the morning of discharge was 0.41.  He had an echo that showed normal cardiac function, an MRI that indicated normal ventricular size and function, with minimal or healing and inflammation or mild myocarditis.  During his admission, he had continuous cardiorespiratory monitoring, that did not show any arrhythmias.   Resp: On 2L NC for comfort, no respiratory distress or hypoxia.   FENGI: Regular diet   Neuro: Ibuprofen scheduled and tylenol PRN for pain.  He was initially started on ibuprofen 800 mg every 8 hours, but was starting to have pain prior to being due for medicine every 8 hours so his regimen was changed to 600 mg every 6 hours which controlled his pain adequately.   ID: Myocarditis panel sent with some results still pending.  Thus far, he is CMV negative, EBV IgG was positive but not IgM.  RVP was negative.  This all occurred in the setting receiving the Covid vaccine 3 days prior to presentation, which has been reported as a rare reaction to the Covid vaccine.  At the time of discharge, labs pending results include mycoplasma pneumonia, coxsackie, parvovirus, enterovirus. Etiology of myocarditis remains unclear at this time, could be related to infectious etiology not yet clear to us, vs related to his COVID vaccine prior to admission.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Strong shoulder pain started on Sat 4/17 in the early morning that woke me up. Went away by 10a after taking tylenol and having a coffee. Sun 4/18: pain again woke me up and was more severe. Had to get out of bed to move around as pain was pretty bad. Went to urgent care. Found nothing serious (not a heart attack or clots, etc). Referred me to go see my PCP if it did not resolve in a few days. Thu 4/22: went to PCP. Pain had subsided for the most part, but started having reduced range of motion when lifting arm straight forward...could not get past 90 degrees (straight out) without pain and a feeling of physical binding in the joint. Suspected bursitis. Prescribed a steroid pack and muscle relaxer.  Sat: 4/24: my son noticed my shoulder blade sticking out when attempting to reach for a glass of water while seated. Decided to make appt with an orthopedic. Fri 4/30: went to orthopedic. Took xray. Found no physical damage, trauma, etc. Noticed winged scapula as reason for lack of range of motion. Prescribed physical therapy. Fir 5/14: still same lack of range of motion and no pain. Went to first PT appt. They took range of motion measurements and agreed I was limited. Tested for other pain or signs of trauma and found none. Prescribed a PT regimen.   After my own research combined with symptoms, and no physical trauma as the source. My suspicion is Parsonage Turner Syndrome brought on by the vaccination.
LAB_DATA: Xray on 4/30...no issues found. Physical range of motion measurements at PT appt on 5/14. Limited range confirmed and noted.

I am now three weeks out from my second vaccine and my neck (rt side) is still stuck in spasm, and there is a growing numbness with a few painful spots growing up the right side of my face up to my eye. My Dad is an ophthalmologist, and he examined me. Confirmed the spasms in my neck and diagnosed the cheek numbness as infra-orbital neuralgia. He said he "strongly believes it is from the vaccine". I went back to the original facility the next day  (5/17/21) and am now being referred to an ENT.

I told him I felt like my BP was off. He checked it and I was basically in hypertensive crisis - 196/98. My BP stayed elevated this way for several days, but finally came down the following week. During this time, and continuing for about 2 weeks, I noticed my heart would often race, I felt lightheaded at times, sometimes I felt like I couldn't regulate my body - almost as though I was in constant fight or flight (very random adrenaline rushes). It felt like my autonomic nervous system was completely out of whack. I still don't feel 100% all the time, but am better.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the first Covid-19 vaccination 3/29/21.  A few weeks later my grandkids (who previously had a covid-19 positive illness months prior) came to visit from out of state for a few days.  They were sick with colds.  After they left, I got (presumably) the cold that they had and was sick for about a week.  I postponed my 2nd dose of the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine until it had been 10 days of feeling better (although I did have mild headaches that ibuprofen seemed to quell).  After receiving the the 2nd dose of the Moderna vaccine I began to have severe pain in one or two of my teeth, ear, and eye.  I assumed it was dental related and spoke to my dentist who put me on amoxicillin and scheduled an appointment a week later.  The pain and headaches intensified and I was taking a lot of ibuprofen and acetaminophen (max doses of each) to reduce the pain.  At the time of my dental appointment my symptoms had lessened a bit and the dentist took x-rays that were inconclusive.  She referred me to another dentist specialist who did the same thing and it was also inconclusive which tooth was bothering me or if there was even decay (under 2 crowns).  The second dentist wanted me to come back after NOT taking any pain meds to make a definitive diagnosis.  So, I stopped taking pain meds and the dental pain wasn't coming back.  What DID come back though were the headaches which now I believed were migraine headaches that were treatable with Fioricet (a migraine med).  Eventually, after maybe 14 days after the 2nd Moderna shot, the headaches finally disappeared...and my teeth are fine.
HISTORY: Hypertension (controlled with lisinopril & dyazide above), benign prostatic hypertrophy (low dose tadalafil), arthritis (ibuprofen)

Sequence of Events re Incident  * Patient made his appointment via on- line scheduler  * Patient came in, filled out his paperwork, made no mention of previous vaccine issue on paperwork  * I performed the usual screening of patient, and when I asked him about any previous reactions to immunizations he stated that he had an ?issue with a TdaP shot 4 years ago and passed out in doctor?s office for several minutes.?  He stated the MD told him that ?he had several other issues with the shot so the MD said it was a ?bad batch??.  * I made sure that the patient was comfortable about getting the Covid shot and he agreed that he was fine to get it. At that time the patient did not seem overly nervous about receiving the shot.  * I administered the shot to the patient and he went directly to the seats next to the pharmacy. I asked him to stay there because he had a past issue with another vaccine.  * Approximately 2-3 minutes later, the patient came back, looked troubled and said he didn?t feel well and was feeling the same way as the other shot. I brought him back into the pharmacy immunization room, sat him down and put his head between his knees. I did a quick check on him to be sure he was breathing OK and that there was no apparent allergic reaction.   * After a minute I brought his head back up and put patient into regular seated position. At no point did he completely lose consciousness or faint. I asked him at that point if he wanted me to call an ambulance or a family member and he declined. He sat there in the chair for approximately 15 minutes- part of the time his head was in his hands, part of the time looking at his phone. He asked for a glass of water and I got him one (he had completely drank it by the time he left). I kept checking on him and it seemed like every time he saw me check on him he put down his phone and put his head in his hands again. He could have been embarrassed by the situation, unsure though. I tried to make him as comfortable as possible.  * After 15-20 minutes I asked him if he wanted me to call someone and he said at that point he wasn?t sure he wanted to drive home so he would call his mother to pick him up, which he did.  * I sat down with him for a couple of minutes and explained that this was called a vasovagal response and was quite common (I even empathized with him by explaining that I have the same response when I get blood drawn at the doctor?s office). He seemed to feel a little better after I explained it to him.  * His mother came in 15 minutes later and I brought her back as well. She explained the same thing happened at the MD office 4 years ago and that it was the Meningitis shot, not Tdap. I explained to them going forward that it would probably be best to get his immunizations at the doctor?s office so that he could lay down after the shot and they agreed.  * He and his mother then walked out of the immunization room and left the building. He left under his own power and without assistance from his mother. I gave him a business card and asked him to call me on Sunday to let me know that he was feeling ok.
PRIOR_VAX: Patient said 4 years prior he received a Tdap shot and "passed out for several minutes" but he asked the doctor about it at the

Patient received the 1st COVID vaccine Pfizer, lot #EW0182 EXP 08/2021 at 2:24 PM in her right deltoid muscle. Client alerted EMT in the observation area about 20 minutes into her observation time. EMT responded to the client. Client reported feeling tightness and numbness in her lower extremities bilaterally. Client was to wait in the observation area for 30 minutes due to history of "face swelling" after taking Amoxicillin. The client sought emergency services following this incident, and denies any medications given at the time. Lead RN and Co-lead RN presented to the client at 2:52 PM. The client was escorted to the anti-gravity chair by EMT. Client denied any itching, swelling of her throat, or SOB. No swelling was noted by RN around the patient's face and mouth. Vitals taken by EMT at 2:52PM were as follows: HR: 73, O2 97%, and HR 80. Pupils equal, round, and reactive to light. Client reports a history of hypertension and diabetes mellitus II. Current medications include Aspirin, Lisinopril, Janumet, and Lipitor. She stated that she takes her BP medications in the evening, and hasn't taken a dose since last night. At 2:56 PM, the client was reclined in the anti-gravity chair. Client denied headache, shortness of breath, or chest pain at the time. No erythema/redness or swelling were noted at the vaccination site, right deltoid. Client was offered water at this time. Repeat vitals by EMT at 3:01 were as follows: BP 120/85, HR 73, O2 96%. Physical assessment by RN demonstrated L radial pulse 2+, bilateral pedal pulses 2+. Client stated the "numbness is getting better". Pedal strength equal bilaterally and hand grasp strength equal bilaterally. Client's smile was equal bilaterally. Bilateral pedal capillary refill <2 seconds. Client denies any history of a circulatory disorder or diagnosis. The client reported her last vaccination was a flu vaccination approximately 5 years ago. At 3:04 PM, the client was assisted to a standing position by RN. The client stated she "feels better." Client was then seated again in the anti-gravity chair without assistance. Due to persistent symptoms RN discussed medical treatment options which included calling 911 for further evaluation, or seeking urgent care services. The client declined EMS services and transport to hospital. Client stated she would prefer to seek treatment at a different Hospital with her husband today. Education was provided regarding signs and symptoms of anaphylaxsis, when to seek EMS services, to follow up with PCP within 1 week regarding reaction and BP, V-SAFE. Client voiced understanding of this. Vitals obtained by EMT at 3:11 PM were BP 130/90, HR 76, O2 97%. Client's husband entered the facility. The client and her husband voiced plans to seek services at other Hospital following discharge from the vaccination site. Client was discharged. Client exited the facility with a steady unassisted gait, into a personal vehicle driven by her husband at 2:26 PM.

Arm was really sore, it had heat in it. Tiredness, headache, and then I got numbness on my left toes except my pinky toes. All my toes were numb, it was scary. Then on the sole of near my big toe was numb. I could feel pressure but no feeling. It was a couple of days with tiredness and headache but the numbness in the sole (palm part) of my foot and my toes wouldn't stop and I kept stomping my foot to try to get feeling in it. It's a bit better now but still not the feeling back. Sometimes I would feel even more of the numbness feeling and sometimes less of the numbness. But numbness never went away. I did have stress going on. On the 18th, I then had welts on my whole body. They were everywhere, they were welts and not hives. Under my chest, back and under my arms etc., welts. I took prednisone and Benadryl and I had my Epi-pen but the fact that I wasn't itching and it wasn't hives I decided not to take it. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I have had a prolonged illness ever since 3-4 days after my second Moderna Vaccination on April 9th. Lethargy!   I took some over-the-counter meds to keep the mucus levels to a point I could breath.  but not many nor very often  as I knew those led to elevated heart rate, and I already had that.  Headaches became common, more like icepicks driven into my head.   My GP thought I must have a sinus infection and started me on one type of antibiotics, then switched to Amoxicillin when that didn't work.  Antibiotics did nothing.  My best relief - 2 ibuprofen & a Benadryl taken sparingly so I could sleep.  I coughed up lots of mucus!  1st trip to the Hospital ER on 05/10/2021 came when my temp reached over 100.4  & my heart rate was at 114.  their conclusion:  I was having a bad reaction to the vaccination.  Take Afrin for 3 days & be glad I was vaccinated.  Through multiple freeze then fever sessions starting this past week,  I have started to feel somewhat better.  my sinuses cleared,  most of the coughing has subsided, the headaches are less frequent and intense.  today, 05/18/2021, my heart rate finally dropped below 100 and my Oxygen level is now mid-90's .

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Presented to ED today with complaint of emesis onset this morning. Pt received her second dose of her Covid vaccine on 5/3. Endorses hx of DKA. Denies hitting head, fever, cough, dysuria, nausea, dizziness. She is initially called a sepsis alert secondary to SIRS criteria although I do not think she likely is septic as she has no other illness symptoms but rather either DKA or dehydration from vomiting from viral illness or her history of gastroparesis.  Patient was treated with Benadryl Reglan fluid bolus Rocephin as part of the sepsis protocol and has had improvement in condition. The patient is given IV fluids along with antibiotics for what appears to be a UTI.  She will be admitted to the CDU for ongoing observation and management of her blood sugar as well as her mental status. She has Reglan and Zofran at home but was given refills. She has follow-up with gastro.

Right away, they were watching me because I felt like my throat was tightening up a little bit. My blood pressure sky rocketed. Then I was okay after awhile. They pharmacist said to take some Benadryl when I got home if I needed it. He knew I had taken Claritin D earlier. I was okay though. But the next morning, I was so exhausted I could barely get out of bed. The next day, I was still really tired. On Sunday morning, 10th, it hit me - I woke up at 04:00 in am. Nauseous; light-headed; gastro-intestinal issues; extremely ill. I called my brother in and was afraid to be by myself. I could barely move around to even get water or go to bathroom.  I got through it somehow that day and on Monday I was just maybe a little but that isn't saying much - still severe. By Tuesday, I called the pharmacy - I was so light-headed I thought I was going to pass out and they told me to go to ER and someone took me and doctor said he was seeing a lot of this.  Gave me IV fluids. It was difficult to stay hydrated - they gave me paperwork on what to drink to stay hydrated - Pedialyte - anything that had water in it. I drank Essentia Water, too. I couldn't stay hydrated and I was so light-headed  (kept feeling like I was going to pass out) that I could have gone to ER again two days later. Doctor said take it easy - he said my body was busy making antibodies. That light-headedness for about a week - but I couldn't drive for two weeks because of it - was still so dehydrated. I had a strange sensation - like I was outside my body - I couldn't think straight. I was feeling pain in my back by my kidneys and went to my doctor.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2/13/21 @ 4:45 pm Severe intermittent Headaches began at the 4 hour mark after shot  Prescription pain medications 24/7 did NOTHING to help the debilitating headache pain  2/13/21 Severe Pain in right wrist for 4 hours, chills, for 3 days after shot; but did not continue after the 3 days. Headaches began to get stronger and there was less time in between them; my right ear began to have intermittent fluttering inside; this went on day and night - I could not sleep with the severe headaches and the inner ear noise - both progressively got worse through 3/1/21 when I called ophthalmologist  and complained about my vision becoming blurry and blocked vision in right eye. 3/2/21 ophthalmologist appt revealed a retinal he. CONT: retinal hemorrhage in the right eye and a large floater break off tissue in same eye that  blocked vision.  She did not know if that was connected to the vaccine however I will note that at my annual eye exam with her last Sept 2020; I have NONE of these issues. She told me to come bck in 2 wks to see if bleed continues or gets absorbed and to contact my Doctor ASAP about the headaches as I was crying in pain while in her office. 3/3/21 I began an extremely severe headache @ 2:30 am, did not subside and was taking max amount of pain meds 6x 500 mgs of tylenol per day and 2x Naproxyn 500 mg 2x/day - called my cardiologist as her was the last Dr to see me in person on2/5/21 the week before my 2nd Moderna vaccine on 2/13/21 The triage nurse at the practice asked me questions, then said to come in at 4p, then my Dr heard, and said to come in ASAP - I got to his office at 11am; he came in exam room, took one look at me; and sent me to Hospital Emergency  Still, on 3/3/21, I went to ER with Dr having phoned them in advanced - I had a CT scan of the brain area - they tried IV pain meds but they did not work - they sent me home with referral to Neurologist. THIS WAS NOT MY CHOICE - I had to wait from 3/3/21 with referral from hospital to Dr  neurologist in the hospital system BUT Diagnostic would NOT allow me to make appt with him until they had another referral as well - You CANT make this  stuff up. Finally I had my cardiac Dr/Surgeon send their office a referral and was able to make appt. YES I SUFFERED GREATLY from 3/3/21 in the ER to 3/25/21 on appt day - I wanted and almost went to ER 2 other times inbetween but they couldn't do anything the first time that helped. 3/22/21 Followup appt with ophthalmologist, the retinal hemorrhage in right eye was being absorbed - good news, the floater was still an issue but nothing could be done. I filled her in on the ER visit etc. 3/25/21 First appt with Neurologist after exam and noting my timeline and ER results of which he had access to being with Hospital he prescribed the AMITRIPTYLIN and ordered 2x MRI's of my head. He suspected that this was an "auto-immune" response to the Moderna vaccine. He told me the medication would hopefully help the severity of the headaches and/or duration. Began that night taking the AMITRIPTYLIN and am still on it. 3/26/21, 2x MRI's of the head a Touchstone Imaging. 4/5/21 followup with Neurologist - the MRI's did not show any current clots in the large vessels; I still had headaches although they were hurting the AMITRIPTYLIN kept them tolerable and that medication also makes me drowsy and heavy sleep so I was much better off with the AMITRIPTYLIN as I could not function without it at all. The Dr wanted an additional 2x MRIs of the smaller vessels to completely rule out any clots that could be in those areas 4/6/21 2x MRI's of the smaller vessels at Touchstone Imaging  4/7/21 appt with my gastroenterologist [every  6 months] as one of my underlying conditions and reason for disability is idiopathic acute re-occurring pancreatitis [confirmed diagnosed 1997] this condition makes it difficult for me to digest many oral prescription medications so it adds a layer of difficulty in treatments not to "induce" a pancreatic episode.  My gastro Dr has had me as a patient since 1997 and knows me well - went over all the Moderna issues and he was ok with the meds. 4/8/21 call from Neurologist that the last 2x MRI's of the smaller vessels were clear - no clots - a HUGE relief - he said to continue the AMITRIPTYLIN which dulls the nerve sensing pain; saying being an "auto-immune" response, that IF this Moderna vaccine follows other types of vaccines auto-immune responses, that the severe headaches will hopefully subside from 4-6 months and that I would continue the medication until there are no further headaches. CURRENTLY - I have been taking the AMITRIPTYLIN since 3/25/21 - I still have some severe headaches "push through" However, they are intermittent - I cannot up the dose of the AMITRIPTYLIN as I am already having difficulties with the meds side effects, drowsy and sleepy, dry mouth and eyes, low energy, etc - there is no choice, the meds or crying with headache pain;  FUTURE I have 6/14/21 followup appt with neurologist - that will be the 4 month mark after Moderna 2 vaccine, I pray the  headaches are gone but as of now; they are still with me. OH note, as soon as I began the AMITRIPTYLIN, the ear fluttering  stopped within 2 wks, yay! I also have to carry water for the dry mouth and I use lubricating drops for the dry eyes. Doable!

After each of the two shots, I experienced severe abdominal cramping and aggressively vacating diarrhea, unlike anything I'm used to in my day-to-day life. First I felt a few sharp pangs in my gut, and thought nothing of it. I then needed to spend an extended amount of time in the bathroom, surprising my poor partner who was mid-shower.   I began to feel nausea and worried I was going to throw up, the first time, and at one moment in the steamed bathroom I noticed that my vision started to cloud and fade, as if I was about to pass out, which isn't something I've experienced either.  It passed rather quickly, and partner believed it was food poisoning so I didn't report it. Then it happened again.  Each time it occurred I *think* about 30 hours after getting the vaccine, so when I already thought I was turning a corner on the faux-flu-like   symptoms I was feeling  from the vaccine.    It was still worth it, to get my shots, but I thought I should contribute my tally mark to "crippling, sudden, and cruel diarrhea" to the list of side effects since I haven't heard others really talk about it.

It is clear to many people that the dosage for the 2nd dose of the Moderna shot is calibrated way too high for healthy people. I have received vaccines at various times throughout my life and never experienced side effects this strong. As of this writing I am still in the middle of these side effects.  Economist has been trying to suggest dialing down the dosage for young and healthy people. He is an influential economist and public policy advisor who persuaded the adoption their highly successful first-doses-first regiment for COVID-19 vaccines.   Note that stronger vaccine doses for the elderly and weaker vaccine doses for younger people has long been common for influenza vaccines. That seems like it would make great policy with the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine, as well as with others.  Vaccine hesitancy is understandably very high because the doses are calibrated too high for young and healthy people, resulting in strong side effects. This should be an easy problem to fix.

Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA For the first days following my 2nd shot my side effects where pretty standard.  I tinfoil taste in my mouth after the shot, I had numbness in my left arm during the first night, I felt light headed on the 13th and had a fever over 100 F that evening.  The 14th I was just sort of "floaty" and unfocused. I was fine while sitting, but if on my feet for more than a few minutes I got light headed and had to sit down.  By Saturday the 15th I was pretty much back to normal and felt normal on Sunday the 16th.  I went to work on Monday the 17th and worked a full shift from 5:00AM to 4:00PM without any noticeable side effects (maybe a bit higher fatigue than normal). On Tuesday the 18th everything went to (Bleep)  I had a normal start  arriving at work at 6:00AM and felt fine until about 7:30AM when I noticed that the panel I  had just taken out of my machine looked bent.  I grabbed a straight piece of wood to check it and it was straight.  I then noticed that the line of holes also seemed to bend, that shouldn't happen.  I raised my head and looked around a bit and noticed that everything looked a bit bent, sort of like looking through a fish-eye lens.  It was a mild bending, but there.  I took off my safety glasses thinking maybe they had gotten warped somehow, but it didn't change anything.  Shortly after this I started feeling dizzy and unsteady on my feet.  I reported this to my supervisor who told me to sit down and make sure to drink some fluids and rest during my 8:00AMbreak.  I took a granola snack bar during break and drank half of my thermos of water.  I sat for a good 10 minutes and started feeling better.  I walked rather unsteadily back to my station and finished the job I was running at the tool, sitting down after starting each piece and then standing up to pull it off when it was done cycling.  I got the job finished but still felt light headed and slightly dizzy.  My supervisor told me to go home and I clocked out just before 9:00AM  I went out to my car and rested for a few minutes then went over to the cafeteria to pick up my lunch and rested some more, then went back to the car.  I waited awhile to see if I still felt dizzy and then left at about 9:30.  The drive home is only 5 minutes, so I felt confident I would be OK as long as I took it slow and kept my vision fixed on the road directly in front of the car.  I arrived at home and checked over my Covid-19 EUA and decided to call my vaccination/healthcare provider.  They scheduled me to come in at 1:15PM and see the PA.  I had a light lunch at 11:15AM and then took a nap until 12:30PM.  My son drove me to my appointment, I was fine walking out to the car, and I didn't have any nausea or dizziness while in the car.  When I was first led in the assistant took my weight, pulse, and BP.  Surprise my blood pressure was 164/110!  I've had slightly high blood pressure before, that is why I am on Lisinopril, but it is very mild, this surprised me!  It apparently surprised the assistant as well since she took my BP again to be sure, and got the same result.  I then stayed seated and waited for the doctor.  She showed up a few minutes later and checked my blood pressure again.  This time it was normal.  Weird.   She checked my eye tracking and heart rate and looked in my ears.  General consensus is that it is high blood pressure and possibly inner ear.  Most likely related to my covid-19 vaccine.  She gave me a blood pressure monitoring sheet and told me to go home, rest, and drink lots of fluids. She sent a prescription for some nausea medication to my pharmacy (I haven't been to the pharmacy yet to pick it up). She will call me back to check up on me on Thursday after 4:00PM.  In the meantime, I am to check my BP three times a day and anytime I am having an episode, and write it down on the form she gave me.  I have a BP cuff at home, so no problems doing just that.  I wrote about my symptoms on my Facebook page and got a reply from my daughter that said she had blurred vision issues after her second shot that lasted for almost the whole week.  It may be something genetic.  My son had his second shot on the 16th at 12:45PM.  So far, other than a sore arm, he has shown no side effects at all.  He had the Pfizer vaccine, while I had Moderna.  It may have made a difference.  I am just glad he is doing well.
LAB_DATA: Blood Pressure: 164/110 mmHg ; Temp: 97.1 F ; Pulse: 76 bpm

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA:  immediately upon receiving injection, heart began racing, and what had been a relatively quite ringing in my ears for the past year or two, also immediately became 2-3x louder (maybe even more?), where it has remained ever since (nearly 2 months).  The heart rate settled down within a few second, but the ringing persisted, and has continued.  Before the vaccine, the ringing was a very high pitched, constant tone, like the high pitched tone I used to hear on an airplane sometimes, but it was so quiet that I only noticed when I would wake up in the morning or at other random times when everything around me was very quiet.  Since the vaccine, however, it has become loud enough that it's impossible not to notice it constantly; not so loud that I can't hear other things around me or people talking, but definitely loud enough that it's unmistakably there and can at times be a real distraction to focus and even conversation.

April 30: rash had worsened significantly in size, bumps, and redness. Rash still very itchy.     * began oatmeal baths, eczema cream with 2% colloidal oatmeal May 10: rash had not improved. Informed to take 20mg Pepcid 2x/day and stop using Triamcinolone.     * within a few days of not using Triamcinolone, rash began to improve and become less itchy, less red, and less raised from skin. Continued aforementioned medications and treatments. May 18: rash almost completely gone, areas of breakout no longer pink or raised from skin, itching has mostly subsided.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Menstrual cycle started after the first dose of Moderna. Continued through the entire next month (daily). LAB_DATA: Vaginal exam with ultrasound performed. No polyps found. Blood work performed and hemoglobin was at 9.4, previously was over 13. Cancelled surgery once I learned this was an adverse reaction to the vaccine with tentative plan for July 2021 if this does not improve.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Alerted by vaccination RN at 12:01 PM that the first 8 doses administered of the day had been given in insufficient amount. The RN stated she realized with the last patient of the morning (receiving dose #9) that the syringe was not the 3mL syringe she was used to using, and was in fact a 1mL insulin syringe. She noted that she had been drawing up the vaccine up to 5 (meaning 5 unit, equivalent to 0.05mL) rather than to 50u to give the full dose (0.5mL).  She stated she recognized her error with patient #9 and administered the correct amount (0.5mL) from a 3mL syringe she was used to using.  In addition to contacting COVID-19 provider, the patient was contacted and informed of the incident and asked to reschedule to come back in to receive the full dose (per CDC guidance) as soon as possible. The patient agreed to come in for a follow-up appointment scheduled 5/19.  At the end of the day, when counting dose administered and factoring in the estimated amount of vaccine wasted due to insufficient dosages, there was just under 9 doses accounted for. The vaccinating RN was questioned again to see if there was any possibility any of the initial 8 patients received a full dose of the vaccine without her realizing it. She stated she did not believe she ever drew up the 1mL syringe to 50u nor administered a 0.5mL dose using the 3mL syringe, though she stated she couldn't say for sure. She said the container holding the syringes had each type divided in one compartment and separated from each other. The COVID-19 provider was informed of this information and additional guidance was requested.

Patient received the 1st COVID vaccine (Pfizer Lot #EW0185 expiration 05/22/2021) at 1426. Patient alerted EMT at 1503 that his palms were feeling sweaty, and he was feeling a discomfort in the right side of his chest on inspiration. PHN responded. Patient?s skin was appropriate to skin tone, and warm to the touch. Patient was alert and oriented and was breathing and speaking with an even tone. Vital signs were taken at 1505 (oxygen 99% heart rate 73 blood pressure 156/102). Patient stated that he was feeling anxious about the vaccine prior to receiving it. Vital signs taken at 1510 (Oxygen 98% heartrate 67 blood pressure 138/78). Patient stated that his palms were not sweaty anymore. At 1514 patient stated that the discomfort was a ?little better.? Blood pressure taken at 1516 (136/78). Patient offered water. At 1523 patient stated that he took a sip of the water and the discomfort came back more intense and was a ?burning? feeling traveling up his right lung. Patient pointed to his right collar bone area when asked to point to where the pain was coming from. At no time did the patient complain of difficulty breathing or shortness of breath. Vital signs taken at 1526 (oxygen 97% heartrate 68 blood pressure 150/90). Patient stated that the feeling would come and go. His stepsister who was accompanying him went to grab his mother from outside at 1530. EMS was called at 1537 by PHN. EMS arrived at 1539. Patient and mother refused transport to hospital and signed AMA at 1551. Patient and mother advised to follow up with primary care provider. Mother stated that they were taking him to the hospital as soon as they left. Patient and mother advised that if life threatening symptoms accrue on the way to the hospital to call emergency services. At 1553 the patient stated that the pain was ?gone for now.? Patient left at 1553 with mother and stepsister unassisted with a steady gait. Patient has no medical conditions, is not taking and medications and does not have any allergies.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient told pharmacist he has habit of passing out when giving blood or getting shots.  He was nervous.  He did well getting shot, set in room for 5 min., then moved him to waiting room where I asked him to stay 15-20 more min. Over a few min he looked very pale, we offered him water. (he barely sipped any). after 5 min he started sweating. He did not call for help, but technician on duty saw him put his head in his lap. We both went out to tend to him. While we were talking to him, he passed out. We called 911. While giving vitals and info to 911, he came to before they got on scene.  While paramedics were assessing him, after about 5-10 more min...he passed out again. This time when he came to, seconds later...he projectile vomited on the paramedics.  They tended to him until about 1:15-1:30. PT refused their suggestion and urging to go with them to hospital. Paramedics left him in pharmacy to leave facility on his own will. Pt refused our suggestion to call someone to come pick him up and not drive.  After sitting outside to get some fresh air, PT came through our drive thru to tell us he was much better and leaving Store. We told him we would call and check on him 5/17/2021. We have called now 2 days (5/17/ and 5/18) and can not get him to return our call.
LAB_DATA: 911 Paramedics assessed patient and felt it was all related to anxiety of getting a shot and fear of needles. Especially since this was dose 2 pfizer. Paramedics did not share  patients vitals with the pharmacy team. patient reported having high blood pressure, untreated.

Within a few days after first dose, my blood pressure went up. Normally I am borderline high (135/80). I have a family history, so I take my BP at home. Over the next few days, it continued to climb. On Sunday night, two weeks after the vaccine, I got a terrible headache and visual disturbance. I took my BP and it went up to 220/120. I thought I was having a stroke, but it turned out to be an ocular migraine. I had only one migraine in my life. It was a month after a TBI, 2 years ago. This was much worse, though, and they are continuing. My BP would not go down, so the doctor has me on BP meds, which I also never needed previously. Despite the meds keeping the BP controlled, I am getting ocular migraines almost daily. It spiked again after the 2nd vaccine dose. The ocular migraines became almost daily following the 2nd one. Two pharmacists told me they are hearing this quite frequently (about the BP and the ocular migraines). The migraines in general, even with those who have never had them previously. I posted online, "I got the COVID vaccine," because I was initially excited to get it. When this happened, I posted about the extremely elevated BP and ocular migraines. Many posted about having had similar reactions. I hope they are reporting these things here!
LAB_DATA: EKG; echocardiogram; bloodwork (to ensure there was no damage and if they could determine what caused the BP to shoot-up). Thankfully, all tests were okay. My heart and valves are okay.  These headaches are miserable though!

Since no determination has been received, the case is managed based on the company causality assessment.  Follow-up (06May2021): This is a follow-up solicited report from a non-Pfizer sponsored program from a contactable consumer, based on information received by Pfizer from Amgen, license party for etanercept (ENBREL).  ADDITIONAL INFORMATION RECEIVED ON 06/MAY/2021: In this follow up, it was reported that the patient experienced blood clots pt no longer having issues with clots [PT: thrombosis] while receiving Enbrel, Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector. The patient's current medical condition included low iron. The patient's concomitant medications included covid-19 (corona virus disease -2019) vaccine. On an unknown date, the patient received covid-19 (corona virus disease -2019) vaccine. On an unknown date in FEB/2021, the patient had blood clot (previously reported). Then on an unknown date in 2021, the patient stated that she had no longer having issues with clots. The patient stated that they thought it might be related to covid or covid vaccine. The patient stated that she now was dealing with low iron count and getting infusions. The patient stated she had low iron as a kid. The outcome of the event thrombosis was reported as recovered/resolved. The event thrombosis was resolved on an unknown date in 2021. The reporter declined consent for follow up. No follow up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.  Amgen comment:This individual case report does not change the safety profile of the product.     Amgen Causality Assessment Thrombosis leg is serious and related to etanercept.   The reporter's assessment of thrombosis leg with the suspect product was not provided at the time of this report. Since no determination has been received, the case is managed based on the company causality assessment.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information currently available and the safety profile of the drug there is a reasonable possibility that suspect product etanercept contributed to the occurrence of the event, thrombosis leg. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

Began shivering; Upset stomach; Tiredness; Increased blood pressure / usually 110/65 and this morning it has been 147/75 and 145/75 respectively; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of shivering in a 85-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 6th May 2021, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On 11th May 2021, 5 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced shivering, upset stomach, tiredness and increased blood pressure. On 12th May 2021, the outcome of the shivering was recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the upset stomach, tiredness and increased blood pressure were not recovered/not resolved.   The reporter considered the shivering, upset stomach, tiredness and increased blood pressure to be possibly related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The reporter was the patient. The patient received Shingrix on the right arm. The patient began experiencing side effects that might be related to the Shingrix vaccine.  On 11th May 2021, the patient began shivering that lasted for about 12 hours and then resolved. On the same day, the patient had an upset stomach, tiredness and increased blood pressure that had not resolved till the time of reporting. The patient's blood pressure was usually 110/65 and on 11th May 2021 and on the morning of the reporting date, it had been 147/75 and 145/75 respectively. The patient was going to see his Health care provider on the reporting date. The reporter consented to follow-up via email but did not give permission to contact health care professional.

ANAPHYLAXIS; HOT AND BRUISED SHOULDER; FLUSHING; BODY ACHES; LOSS OF FEELING IN FACE; LOSS OF APPETITE; VOMITING; CAN NOT SLEEP; CAN NOT DRINK WATER; STOMACH FEELS LIKE SODA; SWOLLEN ARM AND SHOULDER; COULD NOT MOVE FINGER; VERY HOT LEFT ARM; LEFT ARM SENSITIVE TO TOUCH; HOT SHOULDER; LOWER BACK PAIN; DEHYDRATED; SORE ARM; RASH; HIVES AND BUMPS AROUND THE INJECTION SITE; WEAKNESS; INJECTION SITE PAIN; HEADACHE; VERY TENDER ARM AND SHOULDER; TERRIBLE NAUSEA; FEVER; LOSS OF TASTE; LOSS OF SMELL; BRUISE ON  LEFT WRIST; PALMS TURNED BLUE FROM CLAPPING; This spontaneous report received from a patient concerned a 40 year old female. The patient's height, and weight were not reported. The patient's concurrent conditions included smoker, non-alcoholic, crohn's disease, heart murmur, chronic vertigo, panic attack disorder, depression, drug allergy, fish allergy, and perimenopause, anxiety and other pre-existing medical conditions included patient had no drug abuse or illicit drug, patient is allergic to all the narcotics, passes large clots of blood during menstruation. The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, batch number: 043A21A, and expiry: unknown) dose was not reported, administered on 06-MAY-2021 13:15 for prophylactic vaccination. Concomitant medication included meclozine for vertigo.  After receiving vaccination the first thing she felt like there was hot lava going down her left arm ( where she got injected) and she could not move her finger then that went away after 10-15 minutes later. they told her that symptom was normal and everyone experience the same kind of symptom. She completely lost her appetite, the smell of food made her sick ever since she got the shot. Patient stated her left arm was very hot, sensitive to the touch, bumpy around the injection site and sore. all these symptoms were the same day of her shot (on 6-MAY-2021). since the injection she had the headache and it wont go away and she still has the headache today. her relative was telling her that her shoulder was hot. she had body aches ( lower back pain and everywhere, the pain was moving though her body). the second day everything got worse; her arm where she received the injection her whole shoulder was black it looks like if someone threw brick at her, she had hives and bumps around the injection site. she cannot sleep, she cannot eat and she cannot drink water. she was tired and she was not feeling good. she had anaphylaxis 30 hours, dizziness, loss of feeling in her face, her heart was racing. she took two tablets of antihistamine to manage the anaphylaxis reaction. 30 hours after the vaccination she has dizziness, wheezing, she had flushing , rapid pulse, she was throwing up for hours then she had to take the antihistamine. On an unspecified date patient had weakness. Patient said that her fever gets worse every day. He had used Prilosec for years off and on, since he was working as a pharmacist and he retired in 2013) and atorvastatin calcium taken for cholesterol from an unspecified date and ongoing (for about a year; he was changed from Zocor because the medication did not get along with his blood pressure sometimes). The patient previously received zocor on an unspecified date for an unspecified indication and experienced did not get along with his blood pressure sometimes. The patient did not receive additional vaccines on the same date or within 4 weeks prior to the COVID-19 vaccine. The patient received the flu (INFLUENZA VACCINE), pneumonia (PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE) and shingles (VARICELLA ZOSTER VACCINE) vaccines all at the end of 2020 (at the age of 84-years-old) for immunization. The patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE; solution for injection; Lot Number: EB8730) via an unspecified route of administration on an 25Mar2021 (at the age of 84-years-old) as a single dose in the left arm for COVID-19 immunisation. In Apr2021 the patient experienced vision changes in right eye/vision complications/getting a dark spot in the bottom part of the vision of his right eye, loss of his peripheral vision, the peripheral vision in his right eye was getting cloudy/eyes go in and out of focus while reading and his vision was getting a little worse. The clinical course was reported as follows: The patient was a retired pharmacist who called to find out whether there had been any reports of vision complications after the COVID-19 vaccine. He received the second dose of the COVID-19 vaccine on 15Apr2021 and as of about 2 weeks ago, the peripheral vision in his right eye was getting cloudy and the patient was getting a dark spot in the bottom part of the vision of his right eye. He did not know if Pfizer had any types of reports on that type of side effect. He made an appointment with his eye doctor for tomorrow, 04May2021. He wanted to have any information that Pfizer might have. He knew that his eye doctor was going to ask him questions to try to determine what was causing the vision changes. He wanted to check with Pfizer before he went to the eye doctor so that he had an answer to the doctor's questions. The patient reported that his vision was getting a little worse. He was now having a little trouble with the computer. He had to refocus every time he moved his eyes. Yesterday, 02May2021, he had what could have been a problem driving. He was driving on the highway and there was a lighted sign. He could not read the sign because it was on the right side of the road. By the time he could focus on the sign, he could not read it because he was right by the sign. Something like that could be a big problem. He reported that his eyes go in and out of focus while reading. He had to re-focus when he was going to the next line of text that he was reading. He just got an eye exam and new glasses in Feb2021. His problem in Feb2021 was with focus. He was having problems more or less with reading. In the bright light, everything was fine, but that in regular kitchen or incandescent light, he would only be able to read a paragraph or so. He would then have to refocus in order to read more. It became a real problem and the new glasses that he got were not solving it. The patient stated that the last Pfizer representative he spoke with said that Pfizer did not have any vision changes listed as a side effect of the COVID-19 vaccine that the representative knew of. The Pfizer representative informed the caller that there may have been calls that have come in reporting vision changes, but vision changes were not listed as a side effect yet. The patient stated that he saw about 5 doctors. His primary care physician did not know about the vision changes as the changes had just occurred in the last 2 weeks. The patient had absolutely no reaction to either dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. He did not even have a sore arm following the COVID-19 vaccine injections. The vision changes started about 2 weeks ago and he wanted to wait to see if it was going to clear up before he made appointments with his physicians. He reported that his vision did not clear up and that he was now getting concerned, especially with driving. The adverse events required a visit to the physician office. The clinical outcomes of the events vision changes in right eye/vision complications/getting a dark spot in the bottom part of the vision of his right eye, loss of his peripheral vision, the peripheral vision in his right eye was getting cloudy/eyes go in and out of focus while reading and his vision was getting a little worse were not recovered/not resolved. The patient reported that he did not believe (doubted that) that the COVID-19 vaccine caused his vision changes.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information available the changes in vision in this 84-year old patient is attributed to  patient's advanced age and assessed unrelated to BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE).

endometriosis; fibroids; I recently received my Covid vaccine and about a month later had a hospitalization due to abnormal uterine bleeding; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 35-year-old female patient received her second dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 mRNA VACCINE; lot number: EN5318, expiration date not reported), via an unspecified route of administration on 07Feb2021 09:00 (at the age of 34-years-old) at 2nd dose, single in the left arm for COVID-19 immunisation. Medical history included two C-sections (patient was over a year post-partum from having her last child). Concomitant medication included citalopram hydrobromide (CELEXA) for anxiety from Apr2020 to an unspecified date at 10mg, daily, and from Apr2020 and ongoing at 20mg, daily. Historical vaccine included first dose of BNT162B2 on 17Jan2021 09:30 given intramuscularly for COVID-19 immunisation. The patient reported that recently, she received her COVID vaccine and about a month later, on 13Mar2021, she was hospitalized due to abnormal uterine bleeding. The patient has no significant medical history gynecologically, so she wanted to see if there was any correlation with receiving the vaccine and her abnormal uterine bleeding. The patient further stated that she was bleeding heavier than normal and was hospitalized because she had a heavy uncontrollable bleeding that started on 16Mar2021, and also had larger than normal clots, started on 15Mar2021, which presented like fibroids or endometriosis, however, she does not have any of these. The patient had three episodes. On 16Mar2021, the patient went to the emergency room due to bleeding. The patient was there most of the day and was sent home later on. On 17Mar2021, she went to the emergency room by ambulance and was admitted to the hospital. The patient lost so much blood that she had to have five transfusions. The patient was also treated with blood pressure medications because everything was coming out. While in the hospital, the patient had a uterine artery embolization. After discharge, she followed up with the gynecologist who followed her through the hospital. She had no gynecological history of any kind prior to this. The doctors were unable to give a definite explanation as to why this happened. It may have been hormonal at this time in the patient's cycle. She was over a year post-partum from having her last child and she had two C-sections with no issues. The patient stated that this could be completely coincidental. At the hospital on Mar2021, the patient had labs and an ultrasound. The results were in her patient portal online. She had blood work drawn a few days after hospital discharge ordered by the gynecologist and another blood work several weeks later, ordered by her primary care provider. The patient was placed on Iron 325mg by mouth twice daily and was prescribed pain medication, but the patient never took it. The patient was currently taking doxycycline 100mg tablets every 12 hours for inflammation response from the uterine artery embolization procedure that she had. The patient was unsure if this was coincidence or related. The vaccine was the only thing she can think of that may have been a contributing factor. The patient went to emergency room and was hospitalized due to the events. The patient was discharged from the hospital on 21Mar2021. Outcome of the events abnormal uterine bleeding, and bleeding was recovered on 19Mar2021, for event clot blood was recovered on 18Mar2021, and for other events was unknown.

A female patient of an unspecified age received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Solution for injection), via an unspecified route of administration on an unspecified date, 1.5 weeks prior reporting (batch/lot number and expiration date were not reported) as the 1st dose, single for COVID-19 immunization. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On an unspecified date within an hour after vaccination, the patient had "red arms, heart racing, itchiness, and her eyes swollen shut." She was given diphenhydramine (BENADRYL), and was advised not to get the second shot. The reporter was seeking recommendation on how to proceed; if the patient could take another COVID-19 vaccine instead to complete the vaccination series. It was further reported that the patient had a Pfizer COVID shot a week and half prior reporting and she had a reaction to it, which included "arms turned bright red, heart was racing, and eyes swelled shut" on an unspecified date. They gave her a shot of Benadryl, and then she drove home. She had no problem after that.  She had no trouble breathing. They told her not to get the second shot. So the reporter went and looked for more information and saw on one website that she could go ahead and get the Johnson and Johnson vaccine or just stick with the one Pfizer shot. The reporter was wondering what was the current recommendation for this and wanted to clarify. The reporter stated that this type of reaction was not exactly anaphylactic even though they were considering it as such. The patient recovered from all the events on an unspecified date.  Information on the batch/lot number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on available information, a possible contributory role of the subject product,  BNT162B2 vaccine, cannot be excluded for the anaphylactic reaction  and other reported events.  There is limited information provided in this report.  This case will be reassessed once additional information is available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

Had headaches and felt nauseated; Had headaches and felt nauseated; Had a blood clot in her lungs; she had tripped and fallen; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 68-year-old female patient received the second dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE; solution for injection; Lot Number: EN6206) via an unspecified route of administration on 16Apr2021 at 10:00 ("around 10:00 or so"; at the age of 68-years-old) as a single dose in the left arm for COVID-19 immunisation (the patient was "fearful of the new variants and wanted to be extra protected against those variants.") Medical history included COVID in Dec2020 and uses oxygen (normally used oxygen, but not all the time), from an unspecified date and unspecified if ongoing. Medical history was also reported as none. Relevant family history related to the adverse event was reported as none. Concomitant medications (other products) were reported as none. The patient did not receive prior vaccinations, within 4 weeks prior, or on the same date as the COVID-19 vaccine. The patient previously received iodine contrast dye on an unspecified date for an unspecified indication and experienced anaphylactic shock. The patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE; solution for injection; Lot Number: EN6207) via an unspecified route of administration on (at the age of 68-years-old) as a single dose in the left arm for COVID-19 immunisation and experienced did not feel well, felt achy and nauseated (captured in AER: 2021495492). On 27Apr2021 the patient experienced had a blood clot in her lungs and she had tripped and fallen and on unspecified dates the patient experienced had headaches and felt nauseated. The course of events was reported as follows: "After the second dose of the vaccine the patient felt fine, she felt pretty much okay. She attributed that to her having had COVID back in Dec2020 based on her biological knowledge. She ran this idea past a pharmacist that said that generally people might take the first dose of the COVID vaccine and be fine and then be worse on the second dose. But since she had COVID in Dec2020 her second dose of the COVID vaccine was the problem like how people's antibodies were already built up and had that reaction so that is why she was fine. She was walking out of the hospital on 27Apr2021, there were people that had crossed in front of them very quickly and her foot had hit the foot of a lady that was pushing a gurney. The patient tripped and fell down and she was taken to the emergency room. In the emergency room, a doctor did some tests and shockingly the doctor said that the patient had a blood clot in her lungs. A physician's assistant told the patient that she needed to have a computerized tomography (CT) scan done. The patient needed to go home to take care of responsibilities there, so she walked out of the hospital. She did not know if she had a blood clot in her lungs or not. Her doctor said that the blood clot in her lungs was based off of two blood values. One was the d-dimer that had a reference value of < 500 and her level was 1,079 and the other blood work was troponin-I but it looked like it should be in the normal range because her level was less than 0.03 and the reference range was 0-0.04, so she would think that she would fall into the normal range. The d-dimer one was kind of scary. She had other tests done. They did a regular complete blood count (CBC) on her, another kind of test and another set of blood values but from looking at the results she was only a little low on a couple of things. They did not do the test with the contrast, but they did take an x-ray of her lung. The technician had found out that she had not had a Computed axial tomography (CAT) scan in a while, since she apparently needed them periodically, and she felt uneasy because that technician was urging her to get a CAT scan. The patient she did not know if these results were relevant or from the COVID vaccine. She did not understand this but when she was looking at the lab notice there was a note that the patient should be monitored for B Type Natriuretic Peptide (b/np) levels. It had the reference range on that one but when she read it, it looked like hers lied within the normal range. After the second dose she just had a headache but did not feel sick, but a week later they were telling her that she had a possible blood clot in her lungs. The patient was concerned at this point because she had no reason as to why she would have a possible blood clot. it felt like she was going to die/not feeling great; blood pressure is high, diastolic blood pressure was up to 161; This is spontaneous report from contactable consumer (patient). This 49-year-old female patient received the second dose of bnt162b2 (BNT162B2), via an unspecified route of administration, administered in right arm on 23Apr2021 11:00 (Batch/Lot Number: ER8731) as single dose for Covid-19 vaccine. Medical history included problems with intestines 8 years before, high blood pressure in 2008 or 2009 with diastolic blood pressure usually goes no higher than 109, acid reflux in 2002 or 2003, all ongoing, 13 surgeries including one for a brain aneurysm. Concomitant medications included amlodipine for blood pressure measurement from an unspecified start date to 27Apr2021; hyoscyamine for problems with intestines and ongoing; ondansetron hydrochloride (ZOFRAN) for stomach and ongoing; esomeprazole sodium (NEXIUM) for acid reflux and ongoing. She had no side effects from the first dose of the Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine Injection on 02Apr2021 (Lot Number EP7533) on Right arm for Covid-19 vaccine. She ended up having a pretty bad reaction to the Covid-19 vaccine. The following day after receiving the Covid-19 vaccine, on 24Apr2021, she started not feeling great. Her blood pressure was high, but the lower number usually doesn't go higher than 109. The patient reported that her diastolic blood pressure was up to 161 on 24Apr2021. Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine made her blood pressure go through the roof on 24Apr2021 where they were afraid that she was going to have a stroke or heart attack. The patient was in hospital for blood pressure was through the roof from 26Apr2021 to 27Apr2021. Her blood pressure going through the roof made her felt like she was going to die. She was on amlodipine 2.5 mg and because her blood pressure got so high they adjusted it to 10 mg. Her physician prescribed her Lisinopril 40 mg once daily. Her physician called in the lisinopril 40 mg to the pharmacy when increased patient's dosage of amlodipine from 2.5 mg to 10 mg. Her physician informed her that the Amlodipine takes a week to be effective. She was given lisinopril in the emergency room and that lisinopril is faster acting to lower blood pressure. The patient was now taking both Amlodipine 10 mg and Lisinopril 40 mg once daily in the morning and knock on wood she's been doing fine. Lisinopril did not lower her blood pressure and she had to go back to the emergency room. She ended up having to get beta blockers, meclizine, and lorazepam. All 3 of the medications work together to keep her blood pressure down. Her physician informed her that she should have already gone to the hospital and prescribed an additional high blood pressure medication. The patient reported that the new blood pressure medication didn't work so she went to the emergency room on 26Apr2021. Her blood pressure returned to normal on 07May2021 or 08May2021. Blood pressure spiked on 24Apr2021 and she felt like she was going to die required a visit to emergency room. The patient reported that she went to the emergency room three times. She went to the emergency room on 26Apr2021 and was kept overnight until 27Apr2021. She had to go back to the emergency room on 27Apr2021, after she was discharged. The patient also reported that she went to the emergency room the third time on 28Apr2021. The emergency room staff performed brain tests, X-rays, CT scans, MRIs in Apr2021, and couldn't find any reason for the patient's blood pressure to be elevated. The physicians at the emergency room were assuming that the Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine is what caused the caller's elevated blood pressure because that was the only thing that was different. They performed tons of blood work in Apr2021 while she was in the emergency room and it all came back normal. CT scan abdomen, brain, and chest without contrast on 26Apr2021 and on 27Apr2021, X-ray on 26Apr2021 are all normal. The outcome of blood pressure is high was recovered in May2021. The outcome of other event was unknown
