Leg weakness; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable physician (patient).   An 84-year-old female patient received the second dose of BNT162B2 (Pfizer-Biontech Covid-19 Vaccine) intramuscularly, at single dose, on 13Apr2021, at 12:15, for COVID-19 immunization. Relevant medical history and concomitant medications were unknown. The patient previously, on 23Mar2021, at 12:15, received the first dose of BNT162B2 (Pfizer-Biontech Covid-19 Vaccine) intramuscularly, at single dose, for COVID-19 immunization. After the first dose, on 23Mar2021 at night she could not move her legs. She was not able to stand up on her own and could not navigate her legs. She rushed to the emergency room. It was reported that the patient experienced leg weakness on 23Mar2021 at 01:00. The patient recovered from leg weakness on 23Mar2021. On 13Apr2021, after the second dose, the patient experienced leg weakness. The adverse event was assessed as serious (hospitalization and disability). It was unknown if treatment was received. Clinical outcome of the adverse event (after second dose) was unknown at time of this report.   No follow-up attempts are needed, information about lot number cannot be obtained.; Sender's Comments: Based on the close temporal relationship, the association between the event leg weakness with BNT162b2 can not be fully excluded.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

CONFIRMED IMMUNOLOGICAL VACCINE FAILURE; This spontaneous report received from a consumer concerned a 48year old. The patients height, and weight were not reported. The patients concurrent conditions included diabetes, non smoker and non alcohol use and other pre-existing medical conditions included the patient have no known drug allergies and no illicit drug use. The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, batch number: 1805018, and expiry: 25-MAY-2021) dose was not reported,1 total administered on 20-MAR-2021 to left arm for prophylactic vaccination. No concomitant medications were reported.  On 13-APR-2021, the patient had taken blood test for IgG (Immunoglobulin G) /IgM (Immunoglobulin M) and the results were negative. On 05-MAY-2021, the patient had again taken blood test for IgG (Immunoglobulin G) /IgM (Immunoglobulin M) and the results were negative (confirmed immunological vaccine failure). It was reported that the reporter came to know that the patient was not developing antibodies to the COVID-19. The patient was diabetic and the reporter wanted to know that they can use another brand of covid-19 vaccine. The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient had not recovered from confirmed immunological vaccine failure. This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition). This reported was associated with product Quality complaint: 90000178960. The suspected product quality complaint has been confirmed to be not voided (meet PQC criteria) based on the PQC evaluation/investigation performed. This case is a duplicate of 20210513497.  Following receipt of additional information, it was determined that nullification was required for Manufacturer Case Number [20210513497]. The information indicated that Manufacturer Case Number [20210533028].Therefore, this case Manufacturer Case Number [20210533028] was created to correct the country of primary source. All relevant information will be submitted under Manufacturer Case Number [20210533028].; Sender's Comments: V0: 20210533028-covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s-confirmed immunological vaccine failure. This event(s) is considered not related. The event(s) has a compatible/suggestive temporal relationship, is unlabeled, and has unknown scientific plausibility. There are other factors more likely to be associated with the event(s) than the drug. Specifically: SPECIAL SITUATIONS

The patient didn't report any medical history or concomitant product history.   On 06 Jan 2021 at 12:30, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 025J20-2A) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   On the morning of 07 Jan 2021, she noticed a raised bump on the injection site with 2 more red spot, which went away by 10 Jan 2021. Later on, 13 Jan 2021 again she experienced the secondary reaction as pain in arm and new lump. On 14th Jan which adverse into entire swollen, painful, hot and itchy arm which stretched down to elbow.   A treatment of Keflex was given by ER on 13 Jan 2021 and further she visited an allergist.  Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported.   The events, red raised bump on the injection site and then 2 more red spots , were considered resolved on 10 Jan 2021. Whereas event, swollen, hot, painful, and itchy upper arm stretching down to elbow was not resolved at the time of report.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: No adverse event (No medical History reported.)

The pfizer vaccine created an immune response and since I have this blood disorder I was predisposed to this event occurring from the vaccine (hemolytic anemia/juandice) without knowing it. It was a result of the vaccine. I was told to not get the second shot because there is no guidance, but that I am a high risk individual now. I need medical advice from people who are familiar and know.
LAB_DATA: 43 pages worth of hospital files. I was tested for everything- viral and bacterial infections. Negative for everything. Caused as an adverse reaction from vaccine due to my blood disorder (that I was unaware I had at the time).  I have bloodwork from the day I went to urgent care/er/hospital up to this week as they have monitored my levels due to the anemia and jaundice. My doctor or myself can provide these documents
OTHER_MEDS: Breo Ellipta inhaler, Singulair, Vitamin D
HISTORY: (now discovered since adverse reaction from pfizer vaccine ) Hereditary Elliptocytosis

SYMPTOM_TEXT: A few minutes after my first injection shot, I experienced a wave of nausea, flushing, and a metallic taste. I waited for 30 minutes and was assured everything was stable. During the next several days, I experienced high fevers, nausea, vomiting, myalgia, and minor neuropathy (legs/feet). Over the next few weeks, I continued to have intermittent fevers, nausea, myalgia,  and episodes of numbness and tingling in my hands and feet. I consulted with my PCP on 1/28 to see if I should continue with the 2nd dose and was advised to do so. After receiving the second dose, I experienced a similar reaction as the first, with high fevers, nausea, vomiting, myalgia, and minor neuropathy in my legs and feet. One new symptoms following the second dose was muscle twitching in the legs. Approximately two weeks after the second dose, I experienced acute paresthesia of both legs. It began with a bubbling sensation for two days and then progressed to an abrupt onset of burning and tingling. The muscle twitching in both legs increased and also began to appear in my arms. It is now 3 months past the second dose and I continue to have all over muscle twitching and chronic paresthesias of both legs, arms, hands, and tongue (worse in legs). I also have extreme pain in all of my fingertips,  intermittent electric shock sensations in my face and mouth, and internal vibration/buzzing sensations. My POTS symptoms which I had previously managed with adequate hydration and TriOral rehydration salts (no medication) have all been exacerbated. On a side note, I also experienced two menstrual cycles in both months that I received the vaccine and continue to have spotting between periods. I do not have a history of irregular menstrual cycles or spotting. I am currently scheduled for an ultrasound and endometrial biopsy to further assess these symptoms.
LAB_DATA: 4/2/21 - Ferritin, Iron Studies, A1C, Antibodies SM, RNP, RO, LA, ANA, Rheumatoid Factor, Sed Rate, TSH, Free T4, B12, Protein Electrophoresis 4/13/21 - Magnesium, CMP, CBC, MRI Brain/C Spine/T Spine 5/12/21 - EMG/NCT 5/13/21 - Skin Biopsy

I had the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine shot one on March 16, 2021 and shot two April 13, 2021. I am not sure when the headaches started, but I estimated about two weeks, or about April 9, 2021. The headache on April 23, 2021 was bad enough that my wife called our PCP. My PCP asked me a lot of questions and said for me to get a blood draw and an MRI without contrast STAT. The report dated April 23, 2021 was ?a Large 1.5 cm thick right frontoparietal subdural hematoma with transfalcine right to left herniation measuring 1.0 cm. Tiny parafalcine and left frontoparietal subdural hematomas. Given recent vaccination, consider contrast enhanced MRV to rule out venous sinus thrombosis.? I was ordered to go to the ER where I was admitted the same day. A neurosurgery team performed an operation on April 27 to drain the internal bleeding that had occurred (possibly for over a month). As I was about to be released on April 28, 2021, my heart monitor recorded a ventricular tachycardia (vtac); I exhibited 17 beats of vtac where no Potassium and magnesium levels were present. A cardiology team then got involved. An EKG and ultrasound were taken April 29, 2021. Since there were no recurring issues, I was released on April 29, 2021. I do not know if the spontaneous subdural hematoma or the ventricular tachycardia could have been an adverse reaction to the COVID-19 vaccine, but I thought I should report it.

Patient at the clinic for their first COVID-19 Pfizer vaccine today.    Patient, sister and their mother were scheduling their second dose appointment when the writer heard a "thump" on the ground. The writer turned around to see the patient laying on the ground underneath a chair on her stomach with her eyes closed and not responding to voice command at approximately 1520.    The writer and another nurse immediately rolled the patient to her side, a nurse moved the patient's hair from her face and the patient began to open her eyes. Patient began to become alert after less than 30 seconds of the episode.    Patient remained laying down for approximately 2 minutes and stated she was embarrassed. Patient began responding to verbal commands and questions. Patient then began to go from a sitting and then to a standing position. Patient and her family escorted to the recovery room and assessed, refusing wheelchair transport.   Patient's mother stated no history of this adverse event previously.    Vitals taken x2 (See flow sheet). Nurses performed a head-to-toe focused assessment. Patient A & O to person, place, and time. Pupils equal and reactive to light. Patient asked "what day is it" and responded " The 18th." Patient asked "where do you go to school" and responded appropriately with school location. Patient asked "what is your mom's name" and responded. Patient asked "what is your name" and patient responded with her name. Patient asked "how old are you" and responded "12."  Nurse assessed the back and both sides of the patient's head and witnessed no bumps, bleeding, or swelling. Nurse noted redness and slight swelling on the right eyebrow approximately an inch in length. No laceration or bleeding noted. The patient's mother touched the site and the patient stated that it hurt. Nurse advised the patient to place an ice pack on the site and the patient declined. Patient denies any neck pain, headache, nausea, dizziness, lightheadedness, or trouble breathing. Patient skin warm and pink.   Nurse offered ice, animal crackers, and juice and patient declined.   Nurse offered EMS evaluation to patient mother and the patient's mother declined.   Patient's mother and the patient educated on the s/s of a head injury and allergic reaction and instructed to call 911 or go to the nearest ER. Patient and mother also instructed to follow up with a PCP and inform them of today's episode at their next visit.   The patient and the patient's mother also instructed to ask to be given the vaccine in the recovery room for the second dose at the next appointment.   Patient and family remained at the clinic for 30+ minutes. Patient stated that she felt ok and the patient's mother stated she felt ok to take the patient home.    Patient left in the company of her mother and sister in stable condition without transport assistance out of the clinic.   Patient's mother informed that a VAERS report will be filed and that they may contact her for further follow-up.
OTHER_MEDS: None listed or expressed at the time of event
CUR_ILL: No illnesses listed or expressed by patient or parent.
HISTORY: Uncomplicated Asthma listed as a health condition

She got her vaccine, about a day and a half her arm was sore and itchy. The soreness went away but could see redness in the area, which took about 4 weeks for this to disappear completely.  She had a headache which lasted for a short period of time, and disappeared.  She also had a swollen lymph node along her waste that were sore about 2 days after the vaccine, which also disappeared and had it only for a day or two.   She started noticing a sound, thinking it was in her old house the 2nd week of April, but moved to a quieter neighborhood and still noticed it.  She was reading an article this morning in the paper and realized the sound that she was hearing was tinnitus.  She was only born with one ear and it sounds more like a beeping sound than a ringing, but it continues to bother her.  She does not notice it when she's out driving around from the other noises in the environment but when it's quiet due to the one ear she can hear it.  With only one ear she cannot determine the direction of where the sound is coming from, but does notice it during quietness.  She puts her ear up to the wall to determine where the sound is coming from and plugged her ear, and determine it was from the ear itself.     She is worried about it getting worse or not getting any better with only having the one ear.
HISTORY: Congenital ear abnormality, born with one ear.

Tinnitus - ringing in both ears. No prior condition before receiving the COVID shot.  I received the injection of the Pfizer COVID vaccine (dose #1) at 2:30pm on May 13, 2021 at  the Pharmacy . I had a normal day the remainder of the day (work, errands, taking care of my children, etc.) so either the tinnitus had not yet developed or, because of the external sounds, I didn't notice it. I first noticed it the next morning when I awoke but went about my day (with more external sounds masking it). Later that day, I was in a quiet location and noticed the noise again; I thought it might be an electrical motor humming or something (I was in a public place); it was not.  The sound is a high pitched 'white noise' sound, is continuous, has not improved and is most noticible when in quiet situations (reading, sleeping, working on the computer).   While the government machine convinced me to do my civic duty to receive the first injection, I will not return for the second injection.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient expressed concern that first vaccine she acquired some blurred vision about 2 hours after the vaccine and complained of being tired and slight headache. She was advised at that point to strongly consider following up with her Provider and not getting the booster today. She stated she has a new position in the school system and should get the booster and does not wish to follow up with her PCP. She said she was fine and wanted again to get the vaccine booster.  Vaccine booster, Pfizer Lot: ER8727, was given in pts left deltoid at 10:55. Pt tolerated injection well and walked 10 feet to chair in waiting area, where she was visible to me.  Around 11:05, this RN called patient's name and approached pt, as she was noted to be staring into space and not responding to audible cue of her name. She could appropriately answer her name but had to be redirected to the question of her last name x 2. She appeared confused to place and time. Her friend, was called to her side as per patient's request.  After some coaxing, she was assisted with ambulation to a stretcher in the clinic. At that time she appeared to have an unsteady gait. Her VSs at 1110 were BP-191/109, HR 88, O2 96%.  She was able to follow commands with some cuing. She was also able to lift both arms and legs to gravity with moderate strength to resistance. Pupils were equal, reactive and 3mm. She denied any numbness or tingling anywhere, but did complain of a "weird" sensation in her left posterior scalp. No facial droop noted. Her eyes were noted to be blood shot and she stated they had a burning sensation noted.  VSs at 1115 BP 169/103. HR 82, O2 95%  VSs at 1120 BP 180/95, HR 78, O2 95%, at this time patient was advised of the concern of her elevated blood pressure and that we would continue to monitor for about 10 more minutes to see if it would improve. Cognition now almost back to baseline per friend who was at the patient's side. Patient denied history of high blood pressure in the past, but also states she does not routinely follow up with a Provider.  VSs at 1125 BP 192/85. HR 78, O2 94%, at this time patient advised of concern for high blood pressure and associated symptoms she was experiencing and was advised by myself, her friend and Vaccine Clinic RN, to be taken to the ED for a Provider to look at her and a possible evaluation. Pt sat upright on the stretcher and refused to go to the ER. Her friend asked multiple times if she would like a family member to be called and come pick her up if she was going to refuse going to the ER. Patient then stated she was fine and had to go to the bathroom.  Pt escorted by myself to bathroom, gait appeared steady and pt no longer starring into space. Pt accompanied to the bathroom.    Pt accompanied by friend and myself to waiting area and stated she has an appointment tonight to follow up with a Provider at 1830 for psoriatic arthritis and possible steroids. I asked if I would be able to call and talk to this provider to ensure a better transition of care into the community due to not going to the ER. Pt agreed and came back to sit down with me in the vaccine clinic.  Dr. was called and I spoke to him reviewing the aformentioned event to inlcude the patient's VSs. He agreed that when blood pressure initially 191/109 she should've gone to the ER. He then said since the BP was now192/85 that he was okay with her leaving, driving herself back home and seeing him at 1830 tonight, where he would address her hypertention.  Pt was then with steady gait and back to baseline, per friend, escorted back to waiting room nd to her car, where she stated she was going to drive directly back to home. Pt was instructed multiple times if she had any sensation of confusion, dizziness, blurred vision to pull her car over and call 911, also if issues once home to go to ER. She verbalized multiple times her understanding of this information and again did not want her sister called to come and pick her up.
Bexsero given instead of menveo

Shingles  I am a 54 year old male living in another country. I have developed shingles as diagnosed by my doctor on 17th May 2021. During night between 16th May and 17th May, I developed these shingles rashes.   I had first dose of Astrazeneca vaccine (called Covishield) on 14th April 2021. Nearly a month later I developed shingles. I am Type-2 diabetic for the last 20 years with excellent control and no organ damage so far. Still on 2500 mg metformin chloride per day and 10 mg Jardiance per day. I also have high cholesterol and high triglycerides since 15 years and I am on 10 mg Crestor a day. I also suffer from Hashimoto hypothyroidism (an auto immune condition) since 15 years and take about 70 mcg of levothyroxine a day. I am otherwise a fit person with regular exercise and a BMI of 20.5. I have been taking Vitamin C 500 mg for last 20 years, and regularly take Zinc and Vitamin D. Vitamin D level 60 ng/ml.  Looks like Covid vaccine induces shingles in people with auto immune disorder that was not thoroughly checked and studied due to urgent need of vaccine roll out. If stress reduces immunity and is the reason for eruption of shingles, I have been suffering stress from the last one year due to job loss and threat of job loss. But why Shingles erupted only after Covid vaccination? I should have suffered it earlier! It takes two weeks for covid vaccine to become active which could have caused body to fight it and thus lowering immunity. May be immunity is lowering more than necessary when compared to other vaccines. Advantage is taken by shingles virus due to this lowered immunity and causing shingles.  I have never suffered chickenpox during my entire life as I could have been vaccinated as a child for chickenpox. But I still got shingles now after Covid vaccination.   Four years ago, due to job requirements, I had to take multiple vaccinations such as rabies, etc. At the time I did not suffer shingles? But now only after Covid vaccination from Astrazeneca! Seems quick rollout of vaccine has created additional problems for certain groups of populations.  Luckily, I began treatment within 24 hrs with antiviral medication. My friend suffered from shingles 5 years ago. He complained about terrible shooting pain which is the case with shingles it seems. Surprisingly, so far I have not had any shooting pain, no itching, etc. A mild discomfort and a slight burning sensation on upper left chest, left back where shingles formed. But it shingles as confirmed by doctor. Covid vaccination is inducing new kind of shingles with less pain?

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient reported before the vaccine was administered that she had a history of fainting upon receiving vaccines in the past. As predicted, she fainted within seconds of administering the Janssen vaccine. While unconscious, patient had a few mild head/neck twitches which then progressed to 2-3 full body twitches/spasms before regaining consciousness. Total time unconscious with less than 1 minute. Once fully awake and alert, patient informed me that she had a history of a seizure once before. We gently laid her on the floor and I took her vitals. Vitals were low with BP 90/49, HR 49, and O2 90%. She continued to lay on the floor for approximately 10 minutes before checking her vitals again. At that time, vitals were better with HR 60 and O2 99; I was unable to retake her BP at that time, but patient claimed that it usually was on the low side. She called her mother who agreed to come stay with her to keep watch for more events at her home. A family friend was also called to come pick her up and drive her home. Before leaving, I strongly advised patient to see a doctor to check everything out. Patient just moved here and claims to not have a primary at either location.
PRIOR_VAX: Syncope following every vaccination received

28 minutes after receiving the vaccination, the patient began to experience throat itching. The patient was brought back to the monitoring area and vital signs @0759 BP 138/85, HR 85, SpO2 98% on room air. She denied shortness of breath and chest pain. She was administered diphenhydramine 25mg PO at (reduced dose at patient request) at 0802. Patient was monitored closely, breath sounds clear, no stridor or wheezing, strong pulse on exam. She reported tongue swelling and was administered Epi Pen at 0810. Rapid response was called. Vital signs @ 0815 129/82, HR 94, SpO2 98% on room air. Patient was transported to the ED via Rapid Response team. Patient states that she had COVID-19 infection of November 2020 and was hospitalized for approximately 5 to 6 days. She reports that she did not require high flow nasal cannula, intubation, or mechanical ventilation. That she has had what she terms "long haul syndrome "whereby she has continued to be followed for persistent symptoms of tachycardia and lightheadedness. She states that she awoke in her usual state of health this morning and presented for the vaccination. She did receive it in the left upper extremity deltoid region. She notes about 15 minutes after that she felt the onset of some "scratchiness "in her posterior pharynx. Given that she received both epinephrine and Benadryl a rapid response was called and the patient was transported uneventfully to the emergency department. The patient reports feeling improved but not returned to baseline. As noted in the review of systems she does not report any throat closing sensation, hoarseness, shortness of breath, chest pain, palpitations, lightheadedness, near syncope, nausea, vomiting, or pruritus of the skin. She denies urticaria.

Shortness of Breath        History of Present Illness   Patient is a 64 y.o. yo female presenting to the ED with shortness of breath.  Patient has history of COPD and asthma.  She uses inhaler daily and also uses nebulizer as needed.  She got her first Covid vaccine on March 1.  Approximately 6 days later she spent a significant amount of time around her son-in-law who unknowingly at that time had Covid.  She presents today with worsening shortness of breath, nighttime chills, productive cough.  She also feels that she has been wheezing and using her inhaler recently.  She is concerned that she potentially has Covid and that she may have a more severe version because she got the vaccine and was exposed to someone at the same time.  She endorses some vague right-sided chest pain that is only present while coughing.  Patient is Spanish-speaking only so translator is used for history gathering.        Medical Decision Making     Patient presents emergency department complaints of shortness of breath.  Recently got first vaccine for Covid but shortly thereafter was exposed someone with Covid.  Has been coughing, having nighttime chills, and chest pain with coughing.   Bedside exam reveals stable vital signs other than tachypnea.  Pulmonary exam does reveal diffuse rhonchi and wheezings.  Heart is regular.  Abdominal exam is benign.   We will get CBC, BMP.  Check chest x-ray and EKG.  Will give patient DuoNeb and steroids.  Will check a Covid swab.  I think patient is likely suffering from COPD/asthma exacerbation versus pneumonia.  Potentially triggered by Covid.  She currently is not hypoxic.  Anticipate breathing treatments, reevaluation, and likely discharge home.  Low suspicion at this time for cardiac process given that her pain is only present whenever coughing and she has significant findings on pulmonary exam.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I got my shot on 4/1/2021. I woke up on 4/2/2021 at 6 AM. I didn't feel right. I felt kind of dizzy and lightheaded. I got up and had a few sips of water, but my stomach did not really feel right. I lay back down and fell right to sleep. I woke up again around 11:30 AM. I had a severe headache and sensitivity to light, and I felt really sick to my stomach. I had a cup of chicken rice soup and went back to bed. And then I slept until 8:30 AM on 4/3/2021. I still didn't feel well, so I called the on-call doctor and told him my symptoms. I got there at about 12:00 PM on 4/3/2021, and they took me in. They did blood work and checked my vitals, plus a urinalysis. They gave me an IV, because they thought I might be dehydrated. After all the test results came back, the doctor felt my illness was not caused by the COVID vaccine. I was having a migraine. I've had them previously, but it felt different from prior migraines. The doctor gave me Botox injections. I got home at about 7:00 PM on 4/3/2021.
LAB_DATA: The doctor did blood work, took blood work, and took a urine sample. My blood work came back normal. My urine came back normal. My blood pressure and pulse were elevated, probably because of the pain I was experiencing, according to the doctor.

Currently, complaint of itching and burning at rash sites "at bedtime, but doesn't bother me when my mind is active".  Has not yet sought professional medical evaluation or treatment, but plans to go to emergency department or urgent care center once he has completed a home improvement project.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient had received her 2nd COVID vaccine and was about 10 minutes into her post vaccination waiting  when she began feeling lightheaded, clammy, and nauseated.  She got up and walked over to the staff desk where she continued to feel lightheaded and developed tunnel vision.  Staff got her into a wheelchair and she subsequently lost consciousness.  They noticed brief arm and leg jerking motions.  She had no bowel or bladder incontinence or tongue bite.  There was no postictal period.  She is brought to the ED.   She has had minimal to eat or drink today.  She does note that she has had multiple syncopal episodes in the past including with blood draws and at the dentist.  She currently feels fatigued and slightly nauseated.  She was lightheaded and had difficulty standing after the episode so she was brought to the ED  The episode sounds more consistent with syncope than seizure given the lack of postictal period, no tongue bite, bowel or bladder incontinence.  She likely had some myoclonic jerks due to syncope in an upright position.  EKG shows normal sinus rhythm without evidence acute ischemia or infarct, low suspicion for ACS or malignant dysrhythmia as cause for syncope, particularly since she had a clear prodrome prior to syncope. Symptoms appear most consistent with vasovagal syncope related to vaccination.  Patient feeling improved after rest and p.o. intake.  Able to ambulate steadily in ED.  Appears appropriate for outpatient follow-up.

Pt is an otherwise healthy 20 year old male who presents with 2 weeks of blurred vision in R eye.  The blurry vision developed suddenly 1 week after getting 1st dose of covid vaccine (moderna).  He was seen in ophthalmology clinic on 04/29 and diagnosed with R optic neuritis;    The patient reports that his blurred vision has not improved or worsened since onset.  It affects both his near and far vision in the right eye only.  He denies double vision, eye pain, headaches, nausea, vomiting, numbness, tingling, or weakness.  This has never happened before.  No recent illness including fever, chills, runny nose, cough, or sore throat.  Pt admitted to hospital.   Etiology of his optic neuritis is unclear, but possibility include demyelinating etiology (like clinically isolated syndrome). Infectious etiology was thought to be unlikely given no signs/symptoms of infection and reassuring lab workup.  No family history of similar symptoms reported, making hereditary optic neuritis less likely. Other considerations included other primary ophthalmological disease, although otherwise reassuring ophthalmological exam makes that less likely. Unclear association with COVID vaccination.

I finally got the water and 800mg of ibuprofen went back to bed and slept until 11am, got up no headache but since then I have been experiencing hot flashes daily the rest of March and into April a few in May. I realize that I am of the age to experience hot flashes heading into menopause but this was to coincidental and I had never had hot flashes before.

She denies having any episodes of chest pain at all.  She has never passed out, she has never felt like she was going to pass out, she has never felt like she was out of balance.  She denies any nausea or vomiting during episodes.  She denies any headaches during the episodes.  She does have history of migraines, but has not had one in the last couple weeks.  Her prior resting heart rate was in the 80s per her watch, and lately it has been in the 110s to 120s while awake in 80s while asleep.  Along with the episodes, she also feels some pulsating sensation in her abdomen.  She does not have any abdominal pain.  Today, her heart rate was again in the 200s, but it was worse than before because it lasted about 30 minutes total.  Lately they have been using an app that continuously monitors her heart rate.  Since these episodes started, she has cut down on her caffeine intake and she has increased her water intake.  Does not feel that this helped. She has never had syncope in the past and has never had seizures in the past.  Patient was started on carvedilol which has helped control heart rate and was encouraged to drink fluids. Per primary care team, her current episode of tachycardia was not due to the vaccine.

He reports yesterday morning he was woken from sleep at 3-4 am with severe substernal chest pains that radiated to his arm and neck. This was worsened by laying flat and better if he waked around/pacing. He took ibuprofen and it got better so he went back to sleep. The pain returned about 6 hours later and was getting more severe so he went to see his doctor. There an EKG was abnormal so he was referred to the ED where a work up showed ST elevations c/w pericarditis and an elevated trop I of 24.   The night prior, he reported a low grade temperature. He has not had any more fevers for the past 12-18 hours. He denies any other symptoms such as palpitations, shortness of breath, cough syncope. He denies sick contacts but did have a sore throat 4-5 days ago without any other associated symptoms. He has had recent negative COVID tests while at college.    Of note he did receive the 2nd dose of Pfizer on 5/15 about 24-36 hours before onset of symptoms.    Of note, he does boxing at school and has been participating in work outs until about a week ago.   ED course: EKG w/ diffuse ST segment elevation in V3-V6, I, II, II, AVF. Troponin I 24. Creatnine 1.2 with baseline of 0.5 but BUN WNL (11). CBC WNL, CRP mildly elevated to 3.1, Transferred to another ED.   Second ED Course: BP 120/64  | Pulse 83  | Temp 36.7 C (98.1 F) (Temporal)  | Resp 18  | Wt 76.3 kg  | SpO2 97% exam non-focal, COVID ab notable for +spike neg nuclear capsid consistent with vax but no infection, D-Dimer, procal, ESR, ferritin, Coags all WNL, Trop T elevated to 1.46,, ECG with consistent diffuse ST seg elevations, seen by ped cards who did echo in ED and notable for EF ~50%, admitted to PCICU for further management and treatment  Admitted to the PCICU in stable condition. Placed on telemetry monitoring for the duration of the admission. Started on IV steroids and given IVIG on hospital day 1. Continued on toradol which was switched to motrin on hospital day 2. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Visual disturbance beginning about 2 weeks after the second Moderna vaccination. Saw her primary ophthalmologist who did laser treatment to open the posterior capsules. This did not improve her vision so she was referred to a retinal doctor, Dr, who  did wide angle fluorescein angiography and found widespread retinal vascular occlusions without hemorrhage. 90% infarcted in right eye, 80% infarcted in left eye.  Corrected vision is 20/20 in each eye.  There are peripheral visual field defects, but visual field not done.  Features not consistent with diabetic retinopathy.  Findings confirmed by reporting physician, who feels they resemble Susac syndrome and other cases of post vaccine retinal vascular occlusion of which she is aware.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am 33 and trying to conceive, and I religiously track my menstrual cycle (periods, ovulation, tested hormone levels, and symptoms leading up to and following both).  I have a 28-29 day cycle and it is as regular and consistent as the sun rising every day.  In the days leading up to my period, I always experience tell-tale signs that my period is coming (specifically, back & leg cramping, breast pain & tenderness, and increased emotionalism/weepiness).  I received the first dose of the Pfizer vaccine on 3/30/21.  My period started on 4/16/21 following a normal/standard 28-day cycle. It was lighter and shorter than normal, but I ovulated at the expected time following that period, and it did not seem particularly unusual in any way. I received the second dose of the Pfizer vaccine on 4/22/21. Since that time, I have not gotten a period, nor have I experienced ANY of the premenstrual symptoms that I have experienced before every single period in the last 20+ years. I?m now on day 34 of my cycle, I have not had a period, and I am not pregnant.  As I desperately search for answers on the internet, the CDC and other health authorities consistently say there is ?no evidence? that covid vaccines have any impact on menstrual cycles, despite tens of thousands of women with anecdotal evidence. This is infuriating and completely unacceptable. I NEVER would have been vaccinated had I known it would affect my cycles. It may be temporary, it may not affect fertility directly, but i have zero chance of conceiving this month, because there is no way to track and time my cycle. I am 33, desperately trying to conceive, and not getting any younger.  To not tell women this prior to getting the vaccine, and to ignore it and deny it is even a problem, is absolutely criminal.

His EKG was NSR with short PR and STE I, II, III, AVF, V4-V6  Patient is a 21 y.o. male with no past medical history who got his second dose of COVID (Pfizer) vaccine on Saturday presented with chest pain since Sunday with some pleuritic characteristics. He was found to have a very elevated trop I to 10.7, leukocytosis to 12.2 and STE in I, II, III, AVF, V4-V6. His POCUS in the ER was without significant pericardial effusion and probably normal EF. Differential at this point includes pericarditis vs myopericarditis (there are some myocarditis cases reported in Israel post Pfizer vaccination, predominantly in young male patients) vs less likely ACS. He has no past medical history or exertional symptoms to suggest CAD.  Bedside echocardiogram showed preserved left ventricular systolic function. I received a flu vaccine at a drive-thru vaccine clinic on Friday, October 9, 2020 at approximately 5:15pm, sponsored by my insurance provider. I was sitting in the driver?s seat of my car and the nurse who administered the shot was standing up outside of my car. I received the shot in my left arm. By Sunday afternoon, October 11, 2020, I had a very sharp stabbing pain in my left shoulder. I first noticed it when I was outside with my son and we had to stop the activity we were doing. It hurt so much when I moved that I screamed out in pain. It felt as though part of my shoulder was out of place, and I kept asking my son what injury I was not remembering. I also remember specifically wondering out loud with him if my vaccine may have had something to do with it. Over the course of the next two weeks, the pain intensified greatly, and little by little I seemed to lose my ability to move it. I started icing it, and was working on massaging it, thinking I could move whatever was out of place back where it should be. A week or two after my vaccine seemed to be the height of the pain ? I am not a medicine person at all; however, I was taking ibuprofen several times a day hoping for some relief. At that time, I was only able to lift my arm as high as the kitchen counter and had a lot of difficulty getting dressed. For the next couple of weeks, I continued to medicate and massage, and I started to do my own stretching. My son often helped me as I couldn?t move my arm very much on my own. Sometimes it seemed to offer some relief in the moment and there were hours of time when I thought perhaps things were getting better. Finally after weeks of trying to assist through my pain and lack of movement, my son convinced me to reach out to my doctor?s office to get an appointment. It had been a month since the beginning of symptoms at that time. There was a height of pain and ?frozen-ness? at about week two, followed by a plateau. The pain and range of motion have not changed since that time, despite my self-recovery attempts. PRESENT CONDITION: There is a constant throbbing pain in my shoulder, with intermittent stabbing pain depending on how I move and which direction my shoulder is facing at the time of my movement. Because I have been in pain for many months, the muscles and nerves in my entire upper body are on high alert and are also constantly throbbing ? from my neck, down my left arm, and across my entire shoulder blade area. With my arm out straight, I can only raise it to shoulder level at this time (whether in front of me or to the side). I can only raise my left hand about 6 inches above my head. If I am trying to reach behind my back with my left arm, I can only reach as high and as far as my left back pocket. I had an in-person with a doctor on Friday, April 30, 2021 and was diagnosed with adhesive capsulitis (commonly referred to as frozen shoulder). I have my first appointment with physical therapy on June 1, 2021, so until that time I am continuing to exercise my shoulder as I am able to, treat it with heat and topical ointments, and using hot water and ibuprofen to ease the pain. I am taking cyclobenzaprine periodically to ease my muscles at night and help me sleep.  It is unknown at this time whether the pain will subside and I will regain mobility, or if this is something I will be dealing with for the rest of my life.
LAB_DATA: X-ray of left shoulder was taken on 4/15/2021.  Result:  Mild acromioclavicular and no significant glenohumeral joint osteoarthrosis. Small osteophytes identified. No fractures or dislocations. The visualized left lung is clear.
CUR_ILL: No illnesses at time of vaccination and up to one month prior
ALLERGIES: No allergies to medications, food or other products

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 5/19/2021 client received her first dose of the Pfizer Covid-19 Vaccine (lot #EW0185, expiration 08/2022) at 12:42. Client was found sitting upright in her chair with her mother and appeared melancholy. Client was a 13-year-old female, alert and tracking with her eyes. Client had a chief complaint of headache at 12:48. EMT and RN responded. Client stated that she began to have a headache a few minutes after her observation had begun. This was the client's first dose of the Pfizer vaccine. Client's mother did not report any allergies or medical history. Assessment revealed no hives, rash, discoloration, shortness of breath or other signs of anaphylaxis. Client described a generalized headache with dizziness and stated that she had eaten breakfast this morning. Airway, breathing and circulation were intact. Client denied pain throughout the rest of her body. Vitals at 12:52 were blood pressure 122/74, pulse 84, respirations 18, O2 100% on room air, temperature 97.6*f, lung sounds clear bilaterally, and client was alert and oriented to person, place, date and time. Client's mother consented to allowing the client to lie down for 15 extra minutes but refused to remain for the entire 30-minute additional observation. Client's mother was instructed to seek emergency care or medical attention if condition becomes severe after leaving vaccination site. Client's final vitals were consistent at 13:07: blood pressure 118/78, pulse 84, O2 100% and respirations 18. Client's mother was provided with all vaccine related information and acknowledged that she already knew what signs and symptoms to look for as she was already vaccinated as well. departed facility with her mother at 13:07 with client's mother stating "I have another appointment."

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Around 8:30 in the morning of May 18 2021, my mother was not feeling well and had a headache since she got the second dose of the COVID vaccine the previous day on May 17, 2021 at 2:00pm. She decided to take 2 Tylenol pills, 500 mg each. After a few minutes of taking the pills she developed a sever allergic reaction. Her headache pain was increasing and eventually her face started to swell up immensely.  Her body developed a rash and she started to feel itchy. I called 911, and the ambulance said her vitals were okay, however I decided to take her to the clinic here and they gave her another shot in her leg to "block" (as the doctor described) the reaction. Additionally, the doctors there decided to send her to the hospital right away and they did more tests that the Doctor can describe further. She did stay overnight in the hospital, and with the treatments she received, her symptoms have gone down.
LAB_DATA: Within the Hospital, the doctor did give me a medical report that stated " Patient was admitted to our hospital on 5/18/21 through 5/19/21 for allergic reaction after receiving her 2nd COVID shot. She did experience relatively extreme allergic reaction with skin swelling and breathing difficulty. Her symptoms resolved with appropriate therapy. Please feel free to contact if any questions came up."  The doctor also told my mother that this was a rare case and that her veins swelled up and were dropping liquid. This liquid entered her lungs and could have led to more serious problems if we would have waited.
OTHER_MEDS: 2 Tylenol pills (500 mg each) the morning after the vaccine.
